<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Discover New Anti-Clotting Enzymes In Leech Saliva</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli scientists have reported discovering two enzymes in leech saliva that help keep blood from clotting and may be used to fight blood disorders and facilitate surgery. `` We found two enzymes never reported before: collagenase, which breaks down collagen, and apyrase, which breaks down ADP -LRB- adenosine diphosphate -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigbi </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He said collagen and ADP induce blood cells called platelets to stick together, the first step in blood clotting. He and research partners <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Orevi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amiram </PERSON> <PERSON> Eldor </PERSON> have been studying leech saliva for three years. Scientists have known of the fluid's anti-clotting qualities for a century. Three decades ago, a German scientist isolated and identified hirudin, a protein contained in leech saliva that now is considered the most powerful anti-coagulent agent available. Progress in research was hampered because of the scarcity of leech saliva until a new technique was developed by by <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Galun </PERSON>, a research scientist in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parasitology </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. She prepared arginine, a solution of amino acid, and placed it over a membrane of dried calf intestine. She found that leeches took to the solution as an alternative to blood. After leeches drank their fill scientists squeezed them to force out the liquid, which also contained saliva, and the thirsty leeches went back for more. `` The technique gave us two advantanges,'' <PERSON> Rigbi </PERSON> said. `` We start with a much purer material and we can repeat the process several times.'' He found several small molecules that also contribute to the anti-hemostatic process, the researcher said. `` It seems that the leech has a battery of components which inhibit platelet aggregation by a variety of agents,'' he said. `` This is the lesson we are getting. It may also be a lesson for physicians that a certain balance of drugs is necessary in the treatment of patients suffering blood disorders.'' <PERSON> Rigbi </PERSON> said his team found another enzyme called eglin, which he described as `` an inhibitor of elastase, produced by white blood cells,'' and is trying to identify its chemical components to isolate them from the saliva and reproduce them as drugs. `` We have grounds to believe we will discover some unknown compounds,'' he said. The research has aroused commercial interest and <PERSON> Eldor </PERSON>, who is associated with <ORGANIZATION> Hadassah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, is working on practical applications, <PERSON> Rigbi </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
