<FIRST>r a PM-CoalTheater     04-11 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Theater,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theater Built By Coal Miners Opens As Fine Arts School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When this old mining town was booming with coal, men put aside their picks to construct a theater. Today, the miners are few but the structure still stands _ now as a school of performing arts. And as a proper salute to the people who worked underground in <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, organizers of the school have dedicated it to a famous coal miner's daughter, country singer <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>. `` We want to help promote local talent,'' said artistic director <PERSON> Ilene </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>. `` We want to benefit the community. That's what we're here for, to benefit everyone in the arts.'' The three-story building, named the Miners Live Theater and completed in 1918 by members of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 264 </ORGANIZATION>, was used for labor meetings and vaudeville shows. The theater's past is intertwined with the region's coal-mining history. According to literature about the building, the first mine in this town of 20,000 residents, 15 miles east of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, was established in 1857. The industry led to the town's growth `` and by 1886 a man could walk underground through connecting tunnels between the mines from one edge of the city limits to the other,'' literature says. `` Mining and <LOCATION> Collinsville </LOCATION> were almost synonymous terms.'' The coal-mining industry slowly started to wane, however, and in 1969, Miners Live was sold to a private company, which turned it into a movie house. Two years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Bloomer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amusement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> closed the 700-seat theater and it sat idle until February when <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Spurlock </PERSON> reopened it and decided to bring in live acts and launch a performing arts school and production company. The building still needs plenty of renovation. The seats have red strands of tape covering cracked vinyl upholstery. A walk up the stairs to the balcony shows walls with peeling paint. Elevated box seats flank each side of the stage and an orchestra pit is located in front. By starting the school and hiring big-name entertainers to perform at the site, Ms. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> believes Miners Live will gain recognition. `` My gut feeling is that it's doing well already, that the sky's the limit,'' she said Ms. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said the fine arts school will feature instruction in dance, theater, modeling, singing, music, and playwriting. She has assembled a 25-member staff. So far, 50 students have signed up and classes could start this month at the <ORGANIZATION> Loretta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artistic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, she said. `` It's going to be a launching pad for some professional careers _ hopefully,'' Ms. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said. The town is glad to see the doors reopen. Ms. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> was on hand April 1 for dedication ceremonies. `` It was part of <LOCATION> Collinsville </LOCATION> culture for so long,'' Ms. <PERSON> Spurlock </PERSON> said. `` Most people think they have to go to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But like I said, there's nothing in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to compare with what's gon na' be happening here.''
