<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Good day care is expensive for working parents, admits baby guru Dr. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Spock </PERSON>, and he says government and industry are lagging in subsidizing child-care programs. `` There's no reason that the richest country should n't spend money -LRB- on day care -RRB- when they spend trillions of dollars on nuclear arms,'' <PERSON> Spock </PERSON> said at a forum Saturday at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Spock </PERSON>, 84, who wrote his first book about child care in the 1940s, said, `` I still emphasize the child's formative years, but I ca n't stop the tidal wave of women going to work. `` But there are things to mitigate it, to make it work out less harmful,'' he said, suggesting flexible hours and shorter work days as possible ways for parents to spend more time with their children.
