<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polar explorer <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> and his dogsled team greeted well-wishers at a farewell picnic as he and five other adventurers prepared to begin a 2,000-mile south-to-north traverse of <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> this week. <PERSON> Steger </PERSON>, 43, of Ely, is the wilderness guide who in 1986 led the first unsupported dogsled assault to the North Pole. The <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> crossing, expected to take two months, will serve as a test run for his seven-month International Trans-Antarctica Expedition scheduled for August 1989. That journey will be an unprecedented 5,000-mile dogsled traverse across the width of the continent. `` <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> is almost identical to the ice cap we'll have in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> said Sunday. `` For that reason, it's perfect training.'' <PERSON> Steger </PERSON>, his crew and 32 sled dogs will fly Wednesday by cargo plane from <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, for <LOCATION> Narssarssuag </LOCATION>, in southern <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>.
