<HEAD>Jackson, Gore Conciliatory; Cuomo Still Draws Attention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 39-40 bgng: On Sunday ..., with Cuomo
elaborating on draft.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> sounded conciliatory notes Sunday as they campaigned for support in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Democratic presidential primary, a contest in which the active candidates often had to compete for attention with non-candidate <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. Meanwhile, the front-runner in the contest, Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, took the day off to celebrate Greek Easter with his family. Also taking a day off was Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, whose path to the Republican presidential nomination is clear of serious opposition. While <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> rival <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> remains in the race, the former television evangelist has conceded he has no chance to overcome <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s long lead in the race. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> were interviewed on the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> show `` Face the Nation,'' and played down their differences, which have appeared more heated as the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> campaign got under way. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also said that if elected president he would not meet again with <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. He said a meeting he had with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> several years ago was `` for the sole purpose of challenging him to change his posture and move toward a mutual recognition policy with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' That meeting with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has been a focus of criticism of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by Jewish leaders in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> campaigned in heavily Jewish neighborhoods in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Sunday and received the endorsement of state Assemblyman <PERSON> Dov </PERSON> <PERSON> Hikind </PERSON>, who told the crowd, many of them wearing the traditional black hats of the Hasidim: `` We want to understand when one of the candidates has embraced <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>.'' At that, the crowd erupted into loud boos. <PERSON> Hikind </PERSON> described <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> as `` the only one who has had the courage to criticize <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.'' He said that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters were `` telling us we should reward <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for his silence.'' In his brief remarks to the crowd, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> steered clear of comment about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and told the crowd that in his years in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, `` I have stood fast in support of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a strong U.S.-Israeli relationship.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> then took a walking tour for about 10 blocks down 13th Avenue, a street lined with kosher food shops and a variety of other small businesses. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said earlier in the week that Jewish voters and other supporters of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would `` have to be crazy'' to vote for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the primary. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> had made one of the strongest direct attacks of the campaign on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> when he said recently that the nation was looking for leadership not `` a preacher in the White House.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters bristled at the comment and called it racist. Asked if he agreed, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` That's not my basic position. There are race-based questions; his is not a race-based challenge and I accept it in that spirit, in part, because I respect <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> quite a bit as a person.'' When asked if he thought <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> was being unfair, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also demurred. `` No, I think <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has too much character to be categorically unfair,'' he replied. While, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said he had no intention of altering the aggressive tone of his campaign, the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator said he thought all the candidates `` have grown'' during the long debate. As for his approach to the campaign, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said, `` I have no plans to change my basic campaign posture at all.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> spent Sunday morning preaching in the <LOCATION> Abyssinian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, where he delivered a sermon called `` A Letter to Dr. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>.'' He recounted the nation's progress since the civil rights leader's assassination 20 years ago, and said much remains to be done. He concluded quoting King's wish that all people would one day join hands and and sing: `` Free at last ... Thank God Almighty, we are free at last.'' Later, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he could not look up when he read the quote because there is still `` a lot of pain and passion in it all.'' `` All we can do is vow we will continue,'' he told reporters. `` It's not over.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had lunch at a soul food restaurant in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, and walked for several blocks through the neighborhood, hand in hand with his wife <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON>. Residents called out to him and rushed up to shake his hand. People called down from their windows, `` Win, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>!'' and `` God bless you!'' as <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> gave a thumbs-up sign. Security around <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was intense, with about 20 <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police officers escorting him along the sidewalk, along with a phalanx of cameras. Limousines from the motorcade drove alongside. Later, in affluent <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> called for racial unity. ` Even lions and lambs ... do n't want the forest set on fire,'' he told a crowd in affluent <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>. `` If lions and lambs can find common ground, then blacks and Jews, Hispanics and Italians can find common ground,'' he said to cheers from the largely black audience. A young white man waved a sign that said `` Jews want peace with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.'' The common ground in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, as elsewhere in the nation, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, lies in economnic issues and the desire to rid the streets of drugs. Meanwhile, former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, interviewed on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> show, `` Meet the Press,'' commented on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> campaign, saying, `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has not been on the side of Jewish issues'' while all the other candidates `` ca n't wait but line up for those issues all the way down the line.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is `` appealing to those who are restless, despite prosperity. And that is what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must overcome, and that's why I think it's going to be a close election rather than a landslide.'' The former president, driven from office by the Watergate scandal, said that while he would describe <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as `` poets,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would better be compared to `` a word processor.'' On the other hand, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, `` he's cool, he's intelligent, he's tough, he's good in debates He's going to be a very formidable candidate.'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> governor whom some Democrats have urged to get into the presidential race, took the spotlight from the active candidates on Saturday by announcing he would not endorse anyone prior to the April 19 vote and calling efforts to draft him `` unproductive and unwise.'' Did that end the possibility of drafting the governor? `` I've ruled it out,'' he said in a telephone call to The Associated Press. But spokesman <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said the governor meant that a draft should not take place, but was not ruling out acceptance of one if it did occur. On Sunday, however, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said `` I think it is absolutely a reasonable interpretation to say that if a person says it's wrong, it's counterproductive, it's unwise, it should n't be, then that means he rejects a draft.'' When asked if his remarks mean that he would not accept a draft, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said, `` I think so.'' Former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ottinger </PERSON> said Sunday he will suspend his organized effort to draft <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> after receiving a letter from the governor requesting that he do so. He said, however, that if it appears there will be no front-runner at the Democratic convention, the effort would resume. `` It does n't change anything,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, responding to <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s latest comment. `` I'm going to win <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, I'm going to win <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and I'm going to win the nomination,'' said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor who had hoped to get <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s backing before the primary.
