<HEAD>Bomb Damages Base Of Nehru Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb believed planted by Tamil extremists damaged the granite base of a statue of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first prime minister, <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, in the southern Indian city of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. No one was reported injured in the blast on Sunday, the news agency said. There was no damage to the bronze statue of <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, unveiled by his grandson, Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, in December 1987. But chunks of granite were blown out of the base by the explosion. Police told the news agency they found two handbills signed by the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> near the blast site. The group was linked to a bomb blast on a train in the southern Indian state of <LOCATION> Tamil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nadu </LOCATION> in March 1987 that killed at least 22 people and injured 150. <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> is the capital of the state. Tamil speakers in southern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> have long resisted efforts by the government to broaden the use of Hindi, the dominant language in the north.
