<FIRST>r a PM-HighDefinitionTV     04-11 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High Definition TV,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Tech Device Has Industry Excited, Nervous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new age of television promising sharper, brighter images on a larger, wider screen with sound as clean as compact disc recordings is making <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s TV broadcast insdustry excited and nervous. This new technology called high definition TV, or HDTV, is the biggest development in television since the introduction of color and many American TV station owners are eager to explore its potential. They also want to make sure they do n't get left behind. They are watching nervously as competing American interests work toward developing an HDTV transmission standard for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets while the Japanese and Europeans move independently with their own systems, neither of which is compatible with each other or with existing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> TV sets. One of broadcasters' greatest fears is the probability that the Japanese, who plan to offer HDTV in their own country in 1990, will begin exporting to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> HDTV receivers and video cassette recorders. Such packages could cut over-the-air broadcasters out of the video equation and threaten their survival. `` We do n't know how much time it will take'' to develop a system that can be used by over-the-air broadcasters, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, which is developing a system that improves the TV picture though not as significantly as HDTV. `` We do n't know how the audience will react, and we do n't know how much time we have to develop our own HDTV.'' But one thing is certain, he said: `` We broadcasters will have competition by technically superior systems. `` We're fooling ourselves if we do n't think the people in the video cassette, cable and movie industries are going to take advantage of that,'' he warned in a panel discussion at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> convention, which began Saturday and ends Tuesday. `` Broadcasters could be put out of business or severely hurt if we take too long'' to meet the competition with an improved picture, he said. <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> is the most talked about development at this year's convention A room devoted to exhibits of the competing HDTV systems being developed as well as the Japanese system has provided most of the TV broadcasters here their first opportunity to see high definition television. The Japanese have been working on HDTV for nearly 20 years, and they are moving forward quickly. They plan to give a sneak preview of their system with broadcasts of this summer's <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics to <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sets in about 50 big-city department stores throughout the country. The quality of the picture on 35 - and 50-inch HDTV screens is noticeably better than on conventional TV sets The colors are brighter and the detail much greater. And because the width-to-height ratio can be greater, the picture has the panoramic appearance of a movie theater screen. The picture on a standard television set in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is produced by a signal that scans more than 200,000 dots on 525 lines. The Japanese system has 1,125 scanning lines. The Japanese system, however, requires more than the space allocated to TV channels on the electromagnetic spectrum. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the HDTV system called Hi-Vision will be transmitted by satellite to small rooftop antennas, avoiding the bandwidth problem that would be faced by over-the-air broadcasting. But special <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> receivers will be needed to see the enhanced picture. A large part of the debate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is whether a system can be developed that can compress into the standard 6 megahertz TV channel all the electronic information required to produce <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> pictures, or whether additional channel space on another band will be required. Some are advocating a transitional approach in which broadcasters would move first to a system that requires no extra bandwidth and is compatible with existing TV sets and produces an improved picture though not as good as HDTV. Whichever system is ultimately agreed upon by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry, many technical questions must be answered and trade-offs examined. Meantime, many TV station executives are nervous. `` If you're not scared by HDTV, then you do n't understand the problem,'' said <PERSON> LeBon </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON>, vice president and general manager of <ORGANIZATION> KMPH-TV </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` Within a few short years there are going to be high definition systems out there for home use in some fashion,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON>, an engineer at <ORGANIZATION> KKTV-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> `` Broadcasters are most concerned about how that is going to erode their audience.''
</TEXT>
