<FIRST>r p PM-Jackson-Drugs Bjt   04-11 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Drugs, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Questions Hit Home with Young Audience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDANCH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 How many days a week do you practice basketball, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> demanded of the young player prodded to his feet in the packed high school auditorium. `` Four to six,'' was the reply. `` When you come home at night do you study for four hours? ... Three hours? ... Two hours?'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> asked. The other kids were giggling now, and eventually the boy admitted to `` maybe'' one hour of studying, with radio on and occasional calls to his girlfriend. That brought <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to one of his favorite lectures, on the opportunities that await those who study hard, the importance of pushing for all that life holds, of working to rise above less-than-privileged beginnings. Included is a pointed anti-drug and anti-alcohol message that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been hammering home for years to youngsters at schools across the country. `` What does it matter if opportunity is there ... if you're to drunk to stagger through the door?'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> asked. `` What does it matter if your classmate is black or white if you ca n't get along with anybody?'' The motivational talk is not part of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s regular campaign pitch, but talking to high school students is part of his campaign schedule, as it has been a big part of his lecture tours in the past. And fighting drugs is a big part of his campaign message. In talking to the young people, he always includes a dramatic series of questions: How many people here know someone who has died because of drugs? Please stand. A smattering always stand up. How many know someone who is in jail because of drugs? This sometimes brings about half the audience to its feet. How many know someone who has tried drugs? Virtually the entire audience stands. And then <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> asks, `` How many know someone who has contemplated suicide?'' As many as half will stand. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for action against drug use and trafficking gets a more enthusiastic response than almost anything else he talks about on the campaign trail. Lately the candidate has needled his <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> opponents, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, saying they are following his leadership by making drugs a bigger part of their own campaign messages. ` We've never known a threat quite like drugs,'' he told some 4,000 people at <ORGANIZATION> Iona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, on Sunday. In the old days, black people were threatened by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> who came at night wearing hoods and carrying lynching ropes, he said. But now, `` We've lost more lives to dope than to the rope.'' The audience cheered when <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> added his punch line: `` Those who push drugs do n't wear hoods _ they are hoods.'' His standard talk to the high school kids is about more than just drugs _ it's about self-motivation and the chance to excel in life. At <LOCATION> Wyandanch </LOCATION> High, he told the youths that they are good athletes because, ` You do well what you do much. There's nothing wrong with your mind. There's something wrong with your time. ... I challenge you to use your mind. I challenge you to study. Give your mind a chance. `` As I travel around the country, the rising use of drugs and babies making babies and suicide is undermining our opportunity,'' he said. He typically ends up leading a chant: `` Down with dope, up with hope. Down with dope, up with hope.'' The kids, chanting `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>,'' mobbed him Sunday as he left the stage. `` He touched my hand,'' squealed <PERSON> Regina </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, 17. What did she and her friend think of his talk? `` It was very inspirational,'' one of them said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had zeroed in on the problems of their world, especially the `` down with dope, up with hope,'' and the part about `` babies making babies.'' `` That's the problem right here in this school,'' said <PERSON> Regina </PERSON>.
