<HEAD>Crops, Livestock Balance Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the effects of this year's continued improvement in the farm economy may be a closer balance between the crop and livestock sectors, says an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> economist. For some time <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> economists have been forecasting that 1988 net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $ 50 billion to $ 55 billion. Last year, with a bulge in livestock profits, net cash income rose to a record $ 57 billion _ the difference between gross cash income and cash expenses. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says 1988 crop receipts may rise 8 percent to 14 percent from last year's $ 59 billion to a range of $ 64 billion to $ 67 billion. Livestock receipts, which were a record of $ 74 billion in 1987, may decline to between $ 71 billion and $ 74 billion. `` While cattle receipts will be the second or third highest on record, hog and dairy receipts may each fall nearly $ 1 billion,'' he said. `` Substantial increases in supplies could bring hog prices down by one-sixth from last year, and poultry prices one-fourth below two years ago.'' Meanwhile, farm expenses will end their downward trend of the last few years. Feed and fertilizer prices may rise 6 percent to 7 percent in 1988, translating into $ 2 billion of added costs. Repairs, energy and labor could add another $ 1 billion, while interest and livestock purchase may decline by about $ 1 billion. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, writing in the April issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine, said 1988 will bring `` continued improvement in the farm sector's balance sheet.'' A slight strengthening of land prices and a reduction in farm debt of $ 5 billion to $ 10 billion will boost farmers' equity by $ 10 billion to $ 20 billion. `` The combination of higher crop prices, lower hog and poultry prices, and higher feed costs is shifting profits from livestock to crop producers,'' he said. Other impacts of higher crop prices, according to <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, include: _ The turnaround in declining land values coincided with a rise in corn and soybean prices during the first six months of 1987 _ With higher crop prices and the related strengthening in land values, crop farmers have seen larger cash flows and a stabilization of loan security, or collateral, provided by real estate assets `` All regions, including the economically hard-hit <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, are likely to have less farm financial stress in 1988,'' he said. `` Roughly 60 percent of loan default problems of commercial farmers were on primarily crop-producing farms at the start of 1987.'' _ Capital expenditures are picking up as cash flows improve and there is confidence in long-run profit potential In 1988, capital spending may increase by as much as $ 1 billion, with spending for tractors and combines leading the list. _ Government spending on crop supports are easing as commodity prices increase Direct government payments may decline 16 percent to 20 percent this year to between $ 13 billion and $ 15 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five Agriculture Department scientists are being recognized this year for outstanding work during their careers. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the five will be inducted into the agency's Science Hall of Fame at ceremonies on June 21 at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arboretum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> said that each `` has contributed significantly to agricultural or nutritional progress worldwide and has an international reputation for scientific excellence.'' The honors program was begun in 1986 and, with the current nominees, will include 13 <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> scientists. <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> said the 1988 selections are: _ <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, retired microbiologist, Soil and <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrient </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Collins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>, research agronomist and former research leader, <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Stoneville </LOCATION>, _ <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgson </PERSON>, retired national program staff scientist for dairy production, <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, now residing in <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Hamish </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>, senior scientist, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Aging, <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, _ <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Vicente-Chandler </PERSON>, retired research leader and soil scientist, <ORGANIZATION> Soil </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Piedras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> consumers like <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peanuts, if the price is right, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The main competition is from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which provide peanuts for the `` table nut'' sector, the department said in its April issue of Foreign Agriculture magazine. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` splits'' are preferred by processors of peanut butter. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peanuts are liked because they are mechanically harvested and are bought on the basis of a well-understood grading system, the report said. Some improvement has occurred as a result of the rise of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> dollar against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, but the Australian dollar also has dropped sharply against the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> currency. Moreover, the report said, `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peanuts also face a 10 percent tariff in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, while there is no duty on imports from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
