<FIRST>r w PM-FinanceMinisters     04-11 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Finance Ministers,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finance Ministers from 151 Nations Meeting in US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For a change, there's no aura of crisis hanging over this week's meetings of finance officials from 151 nations, a welcome development given the doomsday scenarios which sprang up following the stock market collapse last October. The delegates to the spring meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> will be wrestling with the long-standing problems of Third World debt and huge trade imbalances as preliminary discussions get underway today in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But six months ago, many economists were predicting that the finance leaders would be facing the far more troubling prospect of a global recession, triggered by the stock market plunge. Instead, the world economy is growing at a faster rate than expected, inflation is remaining subdued and the stock markets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries have regained much of the ground lost last fall. For this reason, analysts are n't expecting any major policy changes to come out of the meeting Wednesday between <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and his counterparts from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, the mastermind behind some of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's most successful economic initiatives, is likely to urge a do n't - rock-the-boat approach that will keep things on an even keel through the In a speech last week, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> boasted that `` significant progress'' had been made by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies in promoting economic cooperation. `` The seven largest industrial nations in the free world now have a coordination process firmly in place,'' he said. This will be the first meeting of the so-called Group of Seven since last September. At that time, unity and international economic cooperation were also the watchwords. But behind-the-scenes disagreements between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> over interest rates became public soon after the meeting, unnerving investors and, many believe, contributing to the Oct. 19 stock market collapse. The market collapse served as a strong reminder to finance leaders of the dangers in disharmony and on Dec. 22 they pledged to support the dollar at its current levels. They then backed that pledge up by intervening in currency markets, the process by which governments buy and sell currencies to influence their value. Since early this year, the dollar has stabilized and the top industrial countries are expected to pledge anew this week to support that stability. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is also likely to push again for the other countries to adopt his idea of using an index of commodity prices, including gold, as one of indicators the countries use to measure the impact of their policies. But some have been skeptical, wondering if the proposal might be the first step to moving the world back to a gold standard for currencies, something that was abandoned in 1973 when the current floating exchange rates were implemented. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> denies that, saying the commodity index would merely serve as a useful measure of inflationary pressures. On Third World debt, the finance ministers are expected to basically reaffirm existing strategies although they may adopt some new approaches aimed at cutting the trillion-dollar debt burden. <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, has taken the position that the burden on heavily indebted countries is becoming unsustainable and such initiatives as the recent Mexican debt-for-bonds swap are needed if the debt crisis is ever to be resolved. In that case, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> offered to exchange debt held by commerical banks in return for a reduced amount of Mexican bonds which were backed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury securities. For his part, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has also endorsed efforts to find new ways of reducing the debt burden but he has opposed any broad debt-relief plans involving the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>, contending they would be too costly and would represent a bailout for big commercial banks.
</TEXT>
