<HEAD>McGovern: Dukakis' Win In Wisconsin Should Wrap Up Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former presidential candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> says <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' win in the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary last week will probably assure his receiving the Democratic presidential nomination. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, who lost to former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in 1972, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' win over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary `` was a turning point.'' `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> came out of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> with a head of steam,'' the former <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> senator said. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> talked about the current political campaign Saturday in an interview before he addressed a conference on the Vietnam War. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> finished with 48 percent of the popular vote in the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary Tuesday, compared to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with 28 percent and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> with 17 percent. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, 65, said he has not endorsed any candidate and believes the nomination should go to the Democrat who enters the national convention in July with the most delegates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Time: Bush has ``No Grudges'' Against Rather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he has `` no grudges'' against anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>, with whom he verbally sparred during a nationally televised interview, but he's passed up lunch with columnist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Will </PERSON> because of `` personal attacks,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, discussing his relationship with the media, told the magazine in its current issue: `` I have nothing against <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>. He was nice to my kids. I called him up and said, ` I've been looking for an excuse to call you and say no grudges.' `` The same with many others who have criticized me. They are coming from one place, I am coming from another. I understand that,'' he said in the interview published Sunday. The nine-minute live exchange between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Rather on the `` CBS Evening News'' on Jan. 25, spurred angry phone calls to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> affiliates across the country, as well as headlines and political analysis of the fallout. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, does n't get along with <PERSON> Will </PERSON>, according to Time. `` I draw the line at personal attacks,'' the vice president said. Will called him a `` lap dog'' and then asked him to lunch but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he passed on the invitation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tuesday Caucuses Mark First Step in Missouri Delegate Selection
Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican and Democratic officials alike expect Tuesday's caucuses in which both parties begin their delegate selection process to be relatively quiet events that offer no surprises. Tuesday night, party regulars are scheduled to attend Democratic and Republican meetings to pick individuals to proceed to future gatherings where delegates to the parties' national conventions in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> will be selected. Because <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> had a presidential primary, the number of delegates each presidential candidate will receive already has been determined. So Tuesday night's caucuses will really be a matter of just picking the individuals to represent the candidates. `` There's no reason to try to raid the caucuses,'' said Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Harriett </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, the Democrats' top elected official in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. `` Everybody seems to be magnanimous,'' said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Feather </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's no real animosity.'' Tuesday night's mass meetings are the first of several steps over the next two months that will determine which Missourians will go to the conventions this summer where the two presidential nominees will be picked.
</TEXT>
