<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A one-hour visit planned this week by <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s royal couple has unleashed a wave of monarch mania in <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>. Every lamppost in town has Swedish and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags, a pizza parlor printed special T-shirts for the occasion and inmates were rushing to finish a Swedish farmstead museum in the middle of an abandoned baseball field. `` It's going to be tremendous. <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION> has n't had this much excitement in a long time,'' said <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, the owner of Big <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s Pizza. In honor of the royal visit, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> printed up commemorative Big John T-shirts for some of the 10,000 visitors expected to join King <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> XVI </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustaf </PERSON> and Queen <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> on Thursday. `` That's the closest we'll come to Swedish pizza,'' he said with a laugh. The royal couple plan to start a day of touring in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, where they'll dedicate a log-cabin museum commemorating the historic 1638 landing that led to the Swedish settlement of the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION> normally is not steeped in Scandinavian tradition but the visit kicks off a four-day Swedish cultural tribute that includes dancing, crafts and other events. The visit here is scheduled to last only 60 minutes and will cost about $ 300,000 in public and private funds, city recreation director <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said. But nobody seems to mind the short stop. `` It's more than that. It's a whole weekend but the visit is the highlight,'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal to turn former federal prison <LOCATION> Alcatraz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> into a casino crapped out in a newspaper survey of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> residents. `` I hate to sound so Californian, but it's just not good karma,'' said, one of those surveyed, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, 30. `` It is just a dumb idea.'' The proposal, an advisory measure on the June 7 ballot, was opposed by a margin of 57 percent to 35 percent of the 600 people participating in the poll by the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper reported today. Supervisors who placed Proposition N on the ballot say a casino could generate millions of dollars for the debt-plagued city. Several hurdles would have to be cleared first _ the city would have to acquire the land from the state, the state constitution would have to be changed to allow casino gambling, and numerous capital improvements would have to be made. <LOCATION> Alcatraz </LOCATION>, known as The Rock, now is a popular attraction for tourists who want to take a peek at the former home of gangster <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> and other incorrigibles. Putting a casino on <LOCATION> Alcatraz </LOCATION> `` would be like violating <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rushmore </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Saundra </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>, a legal secretary who moved here from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> 18 months ago. `` I think it is very beautiful. It's peaceful.'' `` The idea of putting some kind of casino blight in the middle of the bay is really repulsive,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. `` Flashing neon just seems like a stupid idea for the bay.''
