<FIRST>r a PM-CountingChimp     04-11 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Counting Chimp,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheba Counting Her Way To Fame</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sheba is n't a typical 6-year-old just because she likes candy, playing with the telephone and coloring. <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> is a chimpanzee who knows how to count. The chimp, who lives at <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s animal laboratory here, is one of only two monkeys in the world able to count, and the only one that understands the concept of zero, said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON>, director of the lab's primate cognition project. <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> said last week she believes that ability is a major step forward in defining the cognitive processes of higher primates and their similarities to those of humans. <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON>, who said the ability to count objects involves a different cognitive process than learning languages, was one of the participants in early studies that showed higher primates can learn language. More than a decade ago, <PERSON> Koko </PERSON>, a female gorilla, and <PERSON> Washoe </PERSON>, a female chimp, learned to use sign language to communicate with humans. But counting is a new research goal, and a hobby <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> indulges in when she is not playing with her keepers, with the four other apes at the lab or with <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON>'s dog <PERSON> Schuyler </PERSON>, who is her best friend. The chimp also dials telephone numbers at random when no one is watching. <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON>, a lab-born chimp owned by The <ORGANIZATION> Columbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION>, will appear on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' this week and is the subject of a People magazine story due out this month. The surrogate mother-daughter relationship between <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Sheba </LOCATION> and their mutual teasing has helped the chimp ignore the attention and get to work. In a recent demonstration, <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> was placed on the floor in front of a small, rectangular yellow plate. Above that was placed plastic squares with numbers ranging from zero to seven, mixed randomly. <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> then placed four apples on the plate. `` OK, <LOCATION> Sheba </LOCATION>. We're going to count some apples. How many?'' <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON>, fighting a desire to mug for a photographer, touched each apple, then pointed to the number five and looked to <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> for approval. `` You know that is not five apples. Try to tell me how many,'' <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> counted again and pointed to the number seven. It took another try and a hallway conference between <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> before the ape finally ignored the photographer and picked the correct number. <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> was rewarded with a kiss and a handful of M & amp; Ms and gumdrops. <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> has worked with <PERSON> Sheba </PERSON> for almost five years, and says the association has been rewarding from the start, even though <ORGANIZATION> Sheba </ORGANIZATION> would rather be playing. `` They have such a short attention span,'' <PERSON> Boysen </PERSON> said. `` At first she would n't try at all. But then she began to show us she could learn fast.''
</TEXT>
