<HEAD>Hot Line Aims To Bring Spies In From The Cold</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to reflect that hot line started one year ago.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT MEADE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A toll-free spy hotline that urges soldiers to report suspicious activity and colleagues who receive phone calls from people with foreign accents has fielded more than 20,000 calls, an official said. But <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>, a civilian <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> employee who for the past year has run the nationwide hotline from a windowless room at <ORGANIZATION> Forte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meade </ORGANIZATION>, says it has not led to any celebrated arrests. `` I know for a fact that there are investigations ongoing,'' <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> said, adding that the calls have sparked several espionage probes by the military and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have heard we have provided significant leads.'' Although the hot line, 1-800-CALL-SPY, is designed for Army personnel across the country, most callers are civilians, <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> said. About 1 percent of the inquiries have provided worthwhile espionage or security-related tips, which are passed on to federal investigators ranging from <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> intelligence to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, he said. `` It's been effective,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ooley </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` The hot line, like any hot line, is an excellent resource for people to report this type of activity,'' <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. Fliers advertising the hot line urge soldiers to watch for colleagues who receive calls from `` someone with a foreign accent'' or `` brag about ... ` <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>' - type Other telltale spy signs are `` a lot of unexplained money'' or odd requests `` for a manual, document or plan.'' The warnings might seem a bit melodramatic, <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> admitted. `` Sound stupid? Yeah,'' he said. `` But these are actual cases.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> says it has concerns about the possibility of abuse. `` It's inviting mischief,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, chief legislative counsel with the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` The allegations can have very serious consequences for someone.'' <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> conceded that the program might appear troublesome. `` Some people look at this and say, ` My God! Big Brother,''' he said. `` That is the furthest thing from our minds.'' Any information received over the phone is checked by several supervisors before it is sent to federal investigators, he said.
