<HEAD>Navy, Families, Mark 25th Anniversary of Nation's Worst Submarine
Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 129 men who died 25 years ago in the nation's worst submarine disaster did not die in vain, the son of one of the victims said at a memorial service. `` Many, many lives have been saved because those guys gave their lives,'' said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> at Sunday's service. His father died aboard the USS Thresher, which failed to surface from a deep dive off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast on April 10, 1963. The 275-year-old North Church was decorated Sunday with Easter lilies and a model of the nuclear submarine the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said could dive deeper and go faster than any other sub in the fleet. Cmdr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoberg </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> chaplain, reminded more than 800 relatives and friends of the dead how <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shipyard </LOCATION> for sea trials 220 miles off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast. `` No scar was visible on the surface of the restless ocean to show where she sank,'' <PERSON> Shoberg </PERSON> said. `` But there would be scars: scars on the hearts of parents without children, wives without husbands, children without fathers.'' As the sub sank water pressure crushed the hull, killing all the men on board. <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON>'s remains lie more than a mile down on the ocean bottom. Retired Rear Adm. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Axene </PERSON>, who commanded the Thresher until three months before the tragedy, shared the task of breaking news of the deaths to the families on April 10, 1963. <PERSON> Axene </PERSON> said Sunday that the Thresher, in his mind, `` remains a mighty ship, manned by a mighty crew still sailing the sea.'' `` She was intended to reach a new peak of perfection. And she did, but the price was very high,'' <PERSON> Axene </PERSON> said. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> board concluded the sub's problems probably started with a leak in saltwater piping. The board said water had shorted out electrical circuits and shut down the nuclear reactor, leaving the submarine powerless. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> developed a program that included stricter construction methods, design improvements, testing for saltwater piping and more initial shallow-water sea trials. <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> read the names of the dead at Sunday's service, which included a 40-minute choral requiem accompanied by harp and violin. When the two-hour memorial ended, the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> offered a 21-gun salute outside the church, while the shipyard sounded a 21-cannon salute and churches tolled their bells. While some cried as they left the church, many people hugged and chatted with friends they had n't seen in years. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, lost her husband <PERSON> John </PERSON> in the tragedy. She attended services with another widow, <PERSON> Edna </PERSON> <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> of Rye, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION> `` The people from Thresher are my extended family,'' said <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> who has not remarried. `` They're your support group. We've been through it all together.''
