<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A two-state public-health alert for pesticide-contaminated cucumbers is in effect in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> following illness in two Seattle-area families. The cucumbers, contaminated with aldicarb, were distributed by wholesalers to grocers in those two states and possibly northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, district director for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Symptoms of the infected cucumbers include nausea, vomiting and diarrhea within one hour of eating, usually within 30 minutes, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said Sunday. Other symptoms can include blurred vision, excessive sweating and muscle twitching. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said officials were unaware of any permanent health damage, adding that the symptoms pass quickly, like influenza. In fact, he said, many people in the area who thought they had the flu in the last week may have actually been suffering from the pesticide. Both cucumber-related illnesses were in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendizabal </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. The health alerts in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> took effect Saturday, although no illnesses were reported in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The cucumbers are European style, 12 to 18 inches long and about 1 -LCB- inches in diameter with pointed ends. They are wrapped in clear, unlabeled plastic, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said. Any skinny cucumbers without labels are considered suspect, said <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, but those with a brand-name label showing they were grown elsewhere are considered safe. The cucumbers were grown in hothouses in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> by Barnard Hydroponic of Redding and distributed by <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anchor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>, an owner of <ORGANIZATION> Barnard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydroponic </ORGANIZATION>, refused to comment in a Sunday telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Redding </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, saying he wanted to talk with <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials first. <ORGANIZATION> Aldicarb </ORGANIZATION> is used to treat soil before crops are grown and is used mostly for non-food crops, including cotton. Use of the pesticide on growing food products is illegal, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said.
