<HEAD>World Court Hearings Open In PLO Mission Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with arguments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> today accused the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration of violating a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> treaty by trying to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Mission in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has asked the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for an opinion on whether the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government must accept arbitration in the dispute, which emanates from anti-terrorist legislation signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last December. That law, which classifies the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> as a terrorist group and bars it from operating on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory, led the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to order the closing of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, a maneuver condemned by all <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> member nations except the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` The -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- secretary-general has the strong desire to avoid any confrontation with the host country,'' a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> undersecretary-general, <PERSON> Carl-August </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischhauer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today. But he stressed that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> `` urges the court to declare that indeed there is an obligation to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOC