<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People seem to be drinking less, and they worry about alcohol more, but health researchers disagree about what it means. `` Overall, there's a clear trend in the direction of moderation,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` In terms of social mores, the public message used to be that it's cool to get smashed. Now, it's dumb to get drunk.'' The cutback in consumption grows in part from recent court rulings in some states recognizing host liability for drunken guests, he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. `` Legal deterrence is a major factor in the moderation, but I think it goes beyond that,'' he said. `` There is just much more informal social pressure not to drink as much.'' But Dr. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wechsler </PERSON>, associate executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said the move to curb excess involves a limited part of society. `` I still think we have a six-pack syndrome out there in much of our society, and the data is there to support it,'' he said. `` Alcohol consumption has dropped, but not markedly and young people are drinking as much as ever.'' <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> legislator Rep. <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bump </PERSON> filed legislation last week to put warning labels on alcoholic beverage containers in the state. `` The bottom line is that alcohol is still the nation's drug of choice and a major health problem, especially among young people,'' she said. A recent Gallup Poll showed that the number of adults who believe that alcohol is a problem in their homes has doubled since 1974 to 24 percent. In 1980, per person consumption was 2.5 gallons of liquor, 2.6 gallons of wine and 30.7 gallons of beer. In 1985, liquor use dropped to 2.2 gallons, beer eased off to 29.6 gallons, but wine consumption rose to 2.9 gallons. <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, co-owner of <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>'s, an Irish pub in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said the bar now sells five cases of nonalcoholic beer weekly, while three years ago there were no takers. `` People are just drinking less, although they're drinking more of the quality stuff,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said, adding that his bartenders now shut off patrons more quickly.
