<HEAD>Experts Worry About 1988 Conditions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs to CORRECT that drought not yet most
severe in last 60 years, picking up 3rd graf pvs; SUBS 13th graf to
CORRECT that reservoirs, not power production, will be 70 to 80
percent of normal this year</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The needs of fish, power generation, irrigation and recreation hang in the balance as a major drought parches the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>. If current conditions continue for another three years, the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> says, the situation could be more severe than the drought preceding the Dust Bowl of the 1930s. The <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> winds 1,243 miles from its headwaters in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> on the Oregon-Washington border. Millions of residents in four states rely on the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and the region's other major river, the 1,038-mile-long Snake, for their livelihoods. Federal fish and power experts say that if the drought continues as expected into 1989, the river system could reach the breaking point. Few of the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>'s 19 major reservoirs are expected to refill this summer, said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, chief of reservoir operations for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>. Even last year, one of the driest on record, was wet enough to fill the man-made lakes. When the rivers run below normal, managers representing Indian tribes, three states and the federal government must decide how to balance competing interests. Controlled flows guarantee safe passage during the annual fall and spring migrations of the salmon and steelhead prized by commercial, recreational and Indian fishermen. The water also spins turbines that light homes and power businesses throughout the region. In good years, the power flows as far as <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, cutting dependence on non-renewable sources of energy. Starting Friday, a fish migration plan developed by the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> calls for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> to flush immense volumes of water down the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and Snake rivers until June 15 for the benefit of spring and summer Chinook salmon smolt. Enough water is stored along the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> for its young fish, but the Snake's flow will not meet this year's goals, according to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Paquet </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. To increase survival, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> plans to use trucks and barges to transport some of the young fish, a move that could avert problems faced in the years following the 1977 drought, when 90 percent of the smolt perished, damaging subsequent fish runs. The receding <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> system will reduce hydroelectric power generated at a series of dams throughout the basin. Reservoirs will be 70 percent to 80 percent full this year, according to <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, manager of system analysis and rates for the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The council says the Northwest's power prospects for 1989 are `` uncertain.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> already has eliminated power sales to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. It has bought power from sources outside the region for the first time in 15 years, said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>, chief of <ORGANIZATION> BPA </ORGANIZATION>'s operations planning branch. For irrigators, the second year of drought has brought critical conditions to several localities, particularly the <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION>, said severe shortages also could occur in southern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, harming onion, seed and fruit crops. Water is less scarce in the potato-growing central areas of the state, he said. Recreational boaters also face problems because of low water levels in the reservoirs.
