<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> showed support Monday for a $ 1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget built to comply with deficit-reduction promises while increasing spending for the AIDS fight, the space program and education. The spending plan cleared an initial parliamentary hurdle 83-0, and debate began at the earliest date in years. Although the law allows 50 hours of debate time, a final vote was considered possible by Tuesday. The smoothness of the process did n't stop an undercurrent of concern and frustration that the election-year plan was n't doing enough about the deficit. `` We're running just a few steps in front of the avalanche of death,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> But given current political constraints, he said, the best the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could do was `` make sure that next year's burden grows no larger. The estimated deficit of $ 136 billion would meet the mandate of the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. But it represents only a modest reduction in red ink from the $ 146.7 billion predicted for the current fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have to `` do much better in the years to come,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, who is retiring after this year. <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the budget committee's senior Republican, drafted the budget in compliance with last fall's deficit agreement between congressional leaders and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The pact set overall spending guidelines and took away what is usually the biggest point of contention _ the balance between domestic and military spending. Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget proposes for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to spend $ 294.0 billion next year. Domestic agencies would spend $ 169.2 billion, while foreign aid would total $ 16.1 billion. The agreement also pre-determined that no new taxes would be included in the budget plan, beyond the $ 14 billion in new taxes enacted last December. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> did in adopting its budget last month, was using the administration's optimistic assumptions about the nation's economy. The non-partisan <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> predicts a deficit some $ 35 billion above the Gramm-Rudman target. Within the overall guidelines of last fall's agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal re-arranges some domestic priorities that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed when he submitted his budget in February. While many domestic agencies will face belt-tightening to absorb inflationary costs, the budget rejects the president's call for eliminating several domestic development and mass-transit programs. It also rejects his request for tightening up in the Medicare system. The deficit-reduction agreement did not cover Social Security or most other benefit programs and none of this year's budget plans has envisioned cuts in those areas The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budgets, like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s proposal, call for big spending increases on the space program, research on AIDS, education and air traffic safety. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan also endorses <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plan to give a 4.3 percent pay hike to the military and only 2 percent for civilian federal workers. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted a 3 percent across-the-board raise. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> must settle on a single budget resolution before it becomes final. The budget resolution is a guideline for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' fiscal legislation, and it does not require the president's signature.
