<HEAD>Endangered Sea Turtles Get Special Treatment Off Cape Canaveral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite the need to keep the entrance channel to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> free for submarine passage, the federal government is taking the slow route in dredging the waterway in order to protect endangered sea turtles. Federal officials have hired a team of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> zoologists to study turtle populations at different times of the year to guide future channel dredging, said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjorndal </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Archie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turtle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> at the university. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> to use only the safest dredging method to avoid harming the turtles, she said. The Corps would like to use hopper dredging, which sucks up sediment with a tremendous hydraulic force, Ms. <PERSON> Bjorndal </PERSON> said Monday. `` The problem is that the sea turtles get sucked up too and torn into pieces,'' she said. The alternative is clam-shell dredging, in which a large bucket slowly scoops up sediment. `` While our work is basic research, it has a great effect on potential management and conservation decisions,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolten </PERSON>, one of the researchers who catch, tag, measure and determine the species and sex of each turtle. The turtles are returned to the water within 30 minutes of their capture. `` A two-day study does n't give you enough information because of the dynamics of sea turtle distribution,'' <PERSON> Bolten </PERSON> said. `` A number of years of data need to be collected for a bigger picture.'' The team did one survey of the channel last month and plans return trips in May and September.
