<HEAD>World Court Hears Flap Over PLO's New York Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American judge on the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should step aside in its dispute with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration over the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official argued before the world court that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is ducking its international responsibility by trying to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission. The diplomatic tug-of-war stems from anti-terrorist legislation signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in December. The law classifies the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> as a terrorist group and bars it from operating on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has tried to use the law to close the 14-year-old mission with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observer status. In Monday's 90-minute session of the world court, American Judge <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwebel </PERSON> challenged a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> claim that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration moves constitute an immediate threat to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s presence in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has said it would wait for a ruling from a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and he said the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should do the same. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deparment </ORGANIZATION> has asked the judge to rule in favor of the closure in a case initially brought by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has asked the world court to issue an opinion against such a closure, which has been denounced by all <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> members but <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> says the dispute should be arbitrated by a special, three-member panel. The world court, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s judicial arm, lacks legal powers to enforce its decisions and can only issue advisory opinions. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary-General <PERSON> Carl-August </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischhauer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> said Monday that the American move to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> office violates a 1947 agreement between the international organization and the <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> administration. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> says that accord, which guarantees the unimpeded functioning of diplomats accredited to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters, also applies to missions with observer status. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was granted permanent observer status at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1974 and has maintained an office near <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> ever since. In a brief released by the court Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATIO