<HEAD>Conference Opens, Archbishop Warns About Environmental Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> told a gathering of the world's religious leaders and lawmakers on Monday that environmental and political problems have imperiled the Earth. `` We are confronted by problems which transcend national and credal boundaries, which are urgent and potentially terminal, and which require not less than a global solution,'' the archbishop told the conference, which is debating global problems. `` We live in a world society which desperately seeks some measure of world community in order to survive,'' said <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, the spiritual head of the state Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and leader of 70 million Anglicans worldwide. In an apparent reference to the plight of hostages in the hijacked Kuwaiti airliner in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> said one crisis that had to be solved was the `` terrorism which fouls and feeds on global communciation.'' <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> took part in the opening of the five-day Global Conference of Spiritual and Parliamentary Leaders on Human Survival. Earlier Monday, the organizers said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> pulled out of the meeting, expressing displeasure at the attendance of the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, the spiritual and temporal leader of Tibetan Buddhism. The conference is a gathering of the leaders of the world's major religions and elected lawmakers and is aimed at putting their influence to work on solving dilemmas such as over-population and poverty In a message of good wishes to the conference, Indian's Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said, `` Those who guide the destinies of spiritual affairs and those who forge the destinies of nations must share the same vision for the betterment of humanity.'' About the pulling out of the Chinese, the Very Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, a co-chairman of the conference, said: `` We worked hard to get the Chinese here because we are discussing issues of great concern to them, like population growth.'' <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> the Divine in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said the leaders of the world's most populous nation had earlier shown a willingness to attend the conference. `` But although we had no formal complaint from the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government about the attendance of the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, we did get a letter from one of their bigwigs saying they were not coming because he was here,'' <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> fled to exile in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1959 after <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> invaded his country and has criticized <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policies in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> is one of a dozen main speakers at the conference. On Tuesday he will address the conference on the universal human condition. He will not attend other sessions of the gathering, which ends Friday. About 200 people from 60 countries in East and West, including the Communist bloc, are attending the conference, with the five main religions of Buddhism, Christianity, <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION>, Islam and Judaism strongly represented. The meeting, apparently the first such religious-political gathering, will discuss how the participants will work together to influence crucial issues, which also include terrorism, urban violence, pollution, conservation and education.
