<FIRST>u a AM-WesternDrought Bjt   04-11 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Western Drought, Bjt,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Low Water Pits Farmers, Utilities Against Fishermen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers, utilities and fish and game officials will be fighting over limited water supplies this summer as a major drought parches the West. `` That's the big concern, the juggling act with water,'' said <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, a fish biologist for the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Wildlife in Central Point. `` There are so many interests in water, what might be best for one interest may not be best for another interest.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> quit selling power to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last fall to make up for a drop in electricity produced by hydroelectric dams on the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> system. But the big victims of the drought will be farmers, ranchers and fish, said <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` The problem is severe on the fish and irrigation side, not the power side.'' In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> already has declared a drought after noting snowpack and reservoir levels were approaching the lows that preceded the drought of 1976-77. `` We've had a critical premature die-off of range land, and lots of water districts are cutting back on farm water allotments,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joaquin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. The snowpack in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> averages 35 percent of normal, forcing some ranchers to sell cattle and appeal for federal grain subsidies as pastures dry up. `` It's scary. It's really scary,'' said <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marr </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Tuolumne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, in the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, which is considering rationing. The West is n't alone. In the Southeast, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> are facing their fourth serious drought in eight years, with some reservoirs at lower levels than they were at this point in the drought years of 1981, 1986 and 1987, officials said earlier this month. `` If we do n't get a dramatic increase in rainfall, we'll be looking at water restrictions this summer,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Word </PERSON>, chief of water resource management for the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, snowpack and rainfall figures range from near-normal in the northwestern part of the state to 36 percent of normal in the south. Ranchers in southeastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> are trucking water to their cattle as water holes dry up, said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> agent in <LOCATION> Lakeview </LOCATION>. Irrigation water will be in short supply for orchards, hopyards, vineyards and livestock around <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, on the drier eastern slopes of the Cascades. In <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, however, unusually heavy rain and snow in March relieved fears of a second year of rationing. Reservoirs are up to 94 percent of normal. The outlook is grim in the region's forests, which were heavily scarred by fires last summer. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Siskiyou </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, where 110,000 acres burned, already has started its fire season. `` Drought conditions do n't guarantee a bad season,'' said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>, who oversees southwest <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION>. `` But they certainly elevate the potential.'' Timber companies worked feverishly over the winter and spring to stockpile logs. `` Companies are concerned that we'll have another serious fire season and they'll be locked out of the woods again,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, timber staff coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regional office in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. Last summer, officials limited logging in high danger areas of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife is particularly worried about a disease called furunculosis killing off thousands of chinook salmon on their spawning run up southern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rogue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Low flows mean warmer water, which promote the growth of the bacteria, said <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>. Low water also makes it tougher for fish to swim up rapids and falls, bottling them up in crowded pools where the bacteria is more readily spread. Starting Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> is to flush immense volumes of water down the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and Snake rivers to help young salmon smolts migrate to the ocean. It also plans to use trucks and barges to carry many smolts around dams, where they can be killed by hydroelectric turbines or spillway torrents. The <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> is facing the prospect of less hydroelectricity from the dams on the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. `` If we have to buy hydropower from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> or if we have to fire up the coal plants in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, which are far more expensive than our hydropower, we are likely to see some rate increases,'' said council spokeswoman <PERSON> Dulcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahar </PERSON>.
