<HEAD>Orange Crop Ahead of Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's orange harvest for the 1987-88 crop season is estimated at 199.4 million boxes, fractionally less than forecast in March but 9 percent more than last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> production, based on April 1 indications, was estimated at 140.6 million boxes, up slightly from March and 17 percent more than last season's crop. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> harvest was estimated at 55 million boxes, unchanged from the March forecast but 6 percent less than in 1986-87. The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> crop was indicated at 2.3 million boxes, down 25 percent from the January forecast, which had been carried forward into February and March, and 27 percent below last season. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> production, at 1.49 million boxes, was down 4 percent from last month's forecast but was up 70 percent from 1986-87's harvest.
