<HEAD>Police Hunt Escaped Murder Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police searched Monday for a murder suspect who drove off in a prisoner transport van after his guards went into a convenience store and left the keys in the ignition. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Letner </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, charged in the torture-murder of nurse <PERSON> Ivon </PERSON> <PERSON> Pontbriant </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, kicked out a passenger-door window in the back of the van and drove away in handcuffs Sunday afternoon, said <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> police spokeswoman <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Letner </PERSON>, 27, drove about a block before using the keys to unlock his shackles and then fleeing on foot. The suspect, who was captured in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and was being returned to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, was one of nine prisoners in the van. Interstate Extraditions of <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, was transporting the men across the country. The private firm uses former law enforcement officers to ferry 3,000 prisoners a year. `` I would certainly consider him very dangerous in light of the escape and because the information from the -LRB- murder -RRB- case alludes to that,'' <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION> police Sgt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Letner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuczek </PERSON>, chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extraditions </ORGANIZATION>, said the prisoner van was en route to <LOCATION> Silver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, before going on to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, but came to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to make four more prisoner pickup stops in <LOCATION> Beeville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. He declined to say if the two guards, with more than 20 years combined law enforcement experience between them, would be disciplined. `` Our procedures indicate that one of the officers should be with the vehicle at all times and that the keys should not be left in the vehicle,'' <PERSON> Kuczek </PERSON> said. `` They -LRB- officers -RRB- were saying that they were hot and needed air and the prisoners wanted the air conditioner to be left on. `` Letner must have been quite an acrobat. We have never had an escape like that,'' he added. Shortly after the guards went into the store, <PERSON> Letner </PERSON> kicked out a rear window and managed to drive the van about a block. He then used other keys on the ring to unlock his handcuffs and shackles, before abandoning the van, authorities said. None of the other prisoners left the van. Helicopters and dogs were used to search for Letner on Sunday, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said, and an all-points bulletin was issued with <PERSON> Letner </PERSON>'s description Ms. <PERSON> Pontbriant </PERSON>'s body was found March 2 in her apartment with a telephone cord wrapped around her neck and several stab wounds, authorities said. Earlier that morning, <PERSON> Letner </PERSON> and another suspect, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobin </PERSON>, 26, had been found in the woman's car, but officials did not know about the killing, <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON> said. About 20 hours later, authorities learned about the slaying and linked <PERSON> Letner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tobin </PERSON> to the killing, <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON> said. The suspects were arrested March 29 in Council Bluffs, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON> said. Two <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION> police officers went to <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> to pickup the prisoners, but because of restrictions allowing only one prisoner per flight, only <PERSON> Tobin </PERSON> was returned to <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON> said.
