<HEAD>Writers Bellow And Terkel Talk To Radio Audience In Kiev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authors <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellow </PERSON> and <PERSON> Studs </PERSON> <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> talked Monday about a familiar topic, writers and writing, but to an unfamiliar audience _ a big chunk of their listeners will tune in on radios in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The topic was `` glasnost'' _ the new policy of openness promoted by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> _ and how writers might help foster greater understanding between their two countries. The program, originating live on public radio <ORGANIZATION> WBEZ </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with panelists commenting by telephone from <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, was recorded for broadcast sometime later this week in that city in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. `` I think we can say the Cold War days have basically had it,'' said <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON>, the Chicago-based author and interviewer known for such books as `` Working'' and `` The Good War.'' `` I'm happy to say that a recent poll ... revealed that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people think drugs is the biggest fear and not communism. It shows there is more curiosity than antipathy when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is mentioned today,'' he said. Panelists in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lauded the more tolerant attitude towards art and artists in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Alexi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gubenko </PERSON>, chief correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kiev </ORGANIZATION>, opened the 75-minute program with an apology to <PERSON> Bellow </PERSON>, the Nobel and Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist whose works have not been ranslated into Russian. `` I can say the ice has already melted in many ways ... Yet, it is very sad that such distinguished w