<HEAD>Spice Imports Rose 12 Percent Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spice imports totaled about $ 439 million last year, up 12 percent from 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The rise was due mainly to larger imports of vanilla beans, white pepper, nutmeg and mace, cassia, cumin, anise, capsicum peppers, laurel and thyme, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. Higher prices of many of the items also were a factor. `` Saffron prices have soared in recent months, reflecting a short Spanish crop,'' the report said. Also, it added, cesium contamination from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s nuclear mishap at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> two years ago `` has kept supplies tight and prices firm for several Mediterranean-area herbs such as oregano, laurel, rosemary and sage.
