<FIRST>r a AM-Drought-Glance     04-11 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Glance,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The anticipated drought in the West this summer will curtail industries and recreation throughout the region. Here is a brief summary:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FARMING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Water districts will cut farm water allotments. Ranchers are trucking water to cattle, selling stock and appealing for federal grain subsidies as pastures and water holes dry up. Wheat farmers are bracing for low yields. Irrigation water will be in short supply for the orchards, hopyards, vineyards and livestock on the eastern slopes of the Cascades in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTILITIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> stopped selling power to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last fall to make up for a drop in electricity produced by the hydroelectric dams on the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> anticipates power rate increases if it has to buy power from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> or generate electricity from coal plants to make up for less electricity from the hydroelectric dams.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FORESTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The region's forests, already heavily scarred by fires last summer, are bracing for fire season. Last summer, officials limited logging in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> forests where the fire danger was high, so timber companies have been stockpiling logs through the winter and spring, pushing up prices in the process.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FISHING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A bacterial disease called furunculosis could kill thousands of spring chinook salmon on their spawning run up southern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rogue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> Low water flows mean higher water temperatures, which promote the growth of the bacteria. Low water also makes it tougher for the fish to swim up rapids and falls, bottling them up in crowded pools where the bacteria is more readily spread.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
