 Rain fell from the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> states on Monday, and cold rain fell over <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, with some snow in higher elevations of western <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. Thunderstorms broke out around <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Thunderstorms produced golfball-size hail at <LOCATION> Peachtree </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Quarter-size hail piled up 3 inches deep at <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION>, in central <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Smaller hail was reported at a number of locations in eastern <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, got 0.71 of an inch of rain in one hour during an afternoon thunderstorm. Temperatures were only in the 40s when scattered rain fell in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, reported a temperature of just 45 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT. The higher elevations of western <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> got more snow, with 3 inches on the ground on the top of <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Mountain </PERSON>, at an elevation of 2,800 feet. A freeze warning was posted overnight for the Hill Country of south-central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, light snow also was reported at <LOCATION> Eastport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, during the afternoon. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38 degrees at <LOCATION> Hyannis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, to 94 at Thermal, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The low for the day was 7 degrees above zero at <LOCATION> 