<SECOND>AM-Food Toxin,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tree May Help Prevent Production of Cancer-Causing Food Toxin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists are looking at the neem tree of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as a possible source of material to prevent the formation of aflatoxin, a naturally occurring food toxin, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Aflatoxin can be produced by fungi that form on some farm crops, including corn and oilseeds. Laboratory tests with animals have shown that aflatoxin is among the most powerful cancer-causing agents known, and <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has called it a `` potential'' hazard to humans. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> scientist <PERSON> Deepak </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> said that as a child in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> his parents often put leaves of the neem tree inside containers of wheat to keep insects from the grain. Now he has found that the leaves also may block fungi from producing aflatoxin. In tests at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> center in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> made solutions containing neem leaves. He found that the solutions did n't kill the fungi but did block more than 98 percent of the aflatoxin they normally would have produced. The fungi that produce the toxin are Aspergillus flavus and A. parasiticus. <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> said the results were `` promising but preliminary'' and that greenhouse studies with cotton are now being planned. The ornamental neem is also known as margosa and nim. More than 80 insect pests, including Mexican bean beetles, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> potato beetles, tobacco budworms and carpet beetles, are repelled by neem extracts.
</TEXT>
