<HEAD>Meese Optimistic About Experimental Herbicide Program against Coca</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for Santa Cruz, Bolivia-dated story on advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental program using herbicides to destroy coca plants is bringing good results and may prove a major weapon against cocaine trafficking, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said Monday. `` <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> has been one of the leaders in the use of herbicides for eradicating coca plants. We have been cooperating with <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> in these experimental studies,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said at a news conference. He later flew to <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, the last stop on his weeklong tour of Latin American countries where drug trafficking is a major problem. His three-day visit to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> will include a trip to the cocaine-producing lowlands of the <LOCATION> Chapare </LOCATION> region. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said he agreed with Peruvian officials that no herbicide should be used on a large scale if it causes ecological damage. `` Early results have indicated the development of a herbicide that does not harm other plants,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said, without providing details. The pilot project using herbicides may eventually replace the system of manually uprooting the plants. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is paying for the experiment. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> on Saturday and toured the <LOCATION> Huallaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> on Sunday. The valley, located on the jungle-cloaked eastern slopes of the Andes, is the center of coca leaf growing in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials say more than 60 percent of the world's coca is grown in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. In the past year the <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION>, a Maoist guerrilla group, has agreed to protect cocaine traffickers in the valley in exchange for a share of the drug barons' multimillion dollar earnings. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> flew low over the valley to observe coca plots, and officials traveling with him said he expressed amazement at the number of clandestine airstrips and jungle clearings where coca grows. Peruvian anti-drug police have blown up more than 170 airstrips since 1985, but most have been repaired in a matter of days by drug traffickers. More than 250,000 Peruvians live by growing coca and processing the leaves into semi-refined cocaine. The coca paste is refined into pure cocaine in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and smuggled to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> began his tour in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> last Wednesday and visited <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> before arriving in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>.
