<HEAD>Amnesty To Be Extended to Aliens Who Overstayed Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced Monday that it will immediately begin accepting applications for amnesty from illegal aliens who overstayed their student and tourist visas. Until further notice, the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> also said it will defer the fee for such applications and issue a temporary work authorization card, in accordance with a court directive. The action is in response to a decision by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> ruled March 30 that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration must broaden its standard for determining whether illegal aliens who had overstayed tourist and student visas can obtain amnesty under the 1986 immigration law. Last week, <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> directed <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> to accept the applications without the customary $ 185 individual filing fee. INS regulations originally stipulated that non-immigrant aliens who overstayed their tourist or student visas must demonstrate that any violation of their immigration status had come to the attention of the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> before Jan. 1, 1982, for them to qualify for the amnesty program. In a ruling on a class-action suit, <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> said the regulation was too restrictive and declared that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended the law to mean that any government record, such as tax or Social Security documents, could be used to document that an illegal alien was known to federal authorities as of Jan. 1, 1982. Immigration experts say the clarifications affect at least 50,000 people. Under the 1986 immigration law, illegal aliens who have been in the country at least since Jan. 1, 1982, may qualify for legalized status. A 12-month application period for the amnesty program is due to expire May 4.
