<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government withdrew thousands of soldiers from the streets of the capital Monday and businesses reopened for the first time after violent anti-U.S. demonstrations last week. Restrictions imposed on two cities under a temporary state of emergency remained in effect, but the government said the emergency might be lifted later this week if no further trouble was reported. Protesters attacked and burned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate Thursday night after a Honduran man suspected of drug trafficking was arrested and flown to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Five Hondurans were killed in the violence. The Honduran Constitution prohibits the extradition of Honduran citizens. The state of emergency imposed Friday gave authorities the power to ban public demonstrations and restrict freedom of movement in the capital of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sula </LOCATION>, 125 miles to the north. The cities are the largest in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Many businesses closed Friday as students filled the street for an anti-American demonstration. They remained shut Saturday as thousands of police and soldiers patrolled the tense capital. Major <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbina </PERSON>, chief police spokesman, said authorities had detained at least 70 people believed involved in the attack on the embassy facilities. Military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the number of people arrested in connection with demonstrations and looting could climb to 300 in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sula </LOCATION>. Thursday night's violence began during a student-led demonstration against the April 5 arrest of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>. Honduran officials took <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> from his <L