<DATELINE>COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> nautical archaeologists excavating the submerged half of <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> found remains of a child killed as he tried to flee during an earthquake nearly 300 years ago, the university said Monday. The partial skeleton of the child, probably no older than 6, was the first found in such a complete state during seven seasons of digging in the sunken city, said project leader <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>. Port Royal, once home to English buccaneers and to a young naval officer named <PERSON> Horatio </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, boasted a well-to-do population of about 8,000 at the time of the quake. But on June 7, 1692, tremors over a period of roughly 30 minutes dropped blocks of the city into the bay, killing 2,000 residents. Nearly 300 years later, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M researchers will resume their archival work on items recovered so far, the university said. The project will be featured May 2 in the PBS series, `` Underwater Discoveries.'' Among other finds from the latest round of excavations is what appears to be part of the living quarters of well-to-do merchants. Remains of a window complete with its slender lead frame have been recovered where the front of a two-story house smashed to the street during one of the tremors, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said. From what is probably the kitchen have come brass cooking pots, sieves, pewter bowls, a woman's gold ring, candlesticks and porcelain dishes. The almost-intact remains of a cricket were found in an unbroken wine bottle excavated where mud had trapped the insect. Port Royal, across the bay from modern-day <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, once was rivaled only by <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> as a center of British commerce in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>. Residents and visitors apparently liked tobacco because a fourth of the nearly 5,000 artifacts recovered have been pipes or parts of pipes. The port never regained its former importance because earthquakes, fires and hurricanes blocked attempts to rebuild, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said.
