<HEAD>Democratic Contenders Voice Support For Notice Of Plant Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential contenders urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to stand firm against administration pressure and retain in its sweeping trade bill a provision requiring employers to give notice of plant closings. `` I offer my strong encouragement to your efforts in resisting any further weakening of these already quite modest provisions,'' <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. `` I urge you and other conferees to insist that mandatory advance plant notification be included in the final version,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Tenn., in a letter to <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> Both messages were dated Friday and released Monday by the office of Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been pushing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to drop the plant closings provision. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> already had called for retaining the provision, which would require companies with more than 100 employees to give 60 days' notice before a plant closing or large-scale layoff. `` I am aware that the administration has refused to accept any form of advance notice provision and has threatened a veto of the trade bill if the conference committee's provision passed,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a March 30 letter to <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. `` I hope that the threat is only that _ a threat that would not be carried out if the situation actually presents itself.'' `` Regardless of the president's intentions, I urge you to work for retention of the plant closing provision in the trade bill,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. The plant closings provision is one facet of a sweeping bill that contains measures ranging from approval for the administration to sign trade deals with other countries to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies. At the heart of the bill are provisions that restructure the way in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> retaliates against violations of international trade rules. Lawmakers say they are designed to open foreign markets to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports. The measure has been approved in large part by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>, although a few finishing touches remain to be attended to. Any congressional move to drop provisions that might yield a veto most likely would have to start with <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> under powers that have been granted him by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, as vice chairman of the conference committee, took the lead in dropping a number of stringent provisions opposed earlier by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The administration has been describing the plant-closings provision as one that would be disastrously expensive for industry. While the measure contains no money provisions, some business groups have suggested it would be a first step toward substantial costs later. The candidates jumped into the debate amid new signals from the administation that a veto could await the 1,000-page trade bill if it arrives at the president's desk with the plant-closings provision intact. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said in an interview on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show that he would meet with congressional leaders early this week to discuss what lawmakers must do to win presidential approval of the legislation. `` At the very least it will take removal of some provisions that are now in that bill,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` Such, for instance, as a provision requiring that any business in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> give prior notice of layoffs or a desire to close a facility.'' He stopped short, however, of saying that a veto would automatically result from trade sanctions in the bill against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> electronics company because of a sale by a subsidiary of submarine-silencing equipment to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` That is something that we do n't like,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` There are a number of things in the bill that we do like. There are a number of things in the bill that we need. I do n't think you can take each and every item in there and say this for sure will trigger a veto. I think you can say that about the plant-closing provision.'' `` My own personal view is that the president will veto the bill if that plant closing provision stays in there,'' he added. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said he hoped to bring the final version of the trade bill to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor for a vote next week. He said that before that happens there may be a few changes in the measure and that he is not `` set in concrete'' on how the provisions are drawn.
