r council officials, nearly $ 3 million was pumped into the organization from <ORGANIZATION> CBN </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, the year <PERSON> Robertsn </PERSON> began establishing his grass-roots campaign organization. Many credit the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, also a tax-exempt, charitable organization, with mobilizing <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s cadre of volunteers, mostly political first-timers drawn mainly from charismatic or fundamentalist churches. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> used these volunteers to pack local <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> meetings and caucuses to gain control of the party at the local level in several states. Under federal tax laws, tax-exempt entities can not raise money for, or support, political candidates. The stated purpose of the council, which closed its operation in October 1986, was to educate Christians on how to get involved in politics. However, critics have charged that the group was a front for <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s then-unofficial political campaign. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> currently is probing the tax-exempt status of <ORGANIZATION> CBN </ORGANIZATION> over the same general issue. If the money was used for <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s campaign, then the tax-exempt status of <ORGANIZATION> CBN </ORGANIZATION> would be in jeopardy. If, as <ORGANIZATION> CBN </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> officials have said, the money was used to educate Christians as to how to become involved in the political process, then it would be legitimate donation. Americans For <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, the campaign organization, filed for organization with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in July 1986. During 1986, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Slosser </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> CBN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, served as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> after retired Gen. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Curry </PERSON> resigned from the post in the spring. When Americans for <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, the campaign organization, was organized in July 1986, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuttle </PERSON> was named acting director. At the same time, he was also a paid consultant for the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nuttle </PERSON> became <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s campaign manager until last month when he was assigned other duties as part of <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s scaling back of his campaign. Though he remains the lone official challenger of Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> admits he has no chance for the nomination. He has laid off most of his national staff and restricted his campaigning to occasional appearances in states that select delegates to the national convention by caucus.
