<HEAD>Israel Deports Eight Palestinians, Orders 12 Others Expelled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with eight Arabs wounded. Picks
up 7th graf pvs ``The deaths ...; SUBS penultimate graf ``Settlers
and...'' with one graf to CORRECT first name to Geulah, sted
Beulah.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> expelled eight Palestinians from the occupied lands Monday, accusing them of inciting the four months of violence there, and it issued deportation orders against 12 others. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, meanwhile, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops shot and killed two Arabs after a group of Palestinians threw stones and bottles at a patrol, the army said. Hospital officials said eight Arabs were wounded. Among the 12 receiving deportation orders were six Palestinians from a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village where an Israeli settler girl and two Arabs were killed in a clash last week. Palestinian leaders contended the purpose of the expulsions was to appease right-wing politicians and Jewish settlers angered by an army report that said <PERSON> Tirza </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON>, 15, was killed by a bullet from another settler's gun. But <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television quoted a top military official as saying the deportations were intended as a warning to Palestinians. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of Rai near <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, troops shot and killed two Arabs after a patrol was pelted with rocks and bottles, the army said. Arab doctors said three other Palestinians, including an 11-year-old girl and a 14-year-old boy, were wounded in <LOCATION> Rai </LOCATION>. Hospital officials said four others were wounded in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION>, another village near <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>. The deaths brought to 143 the number of Arabs killed since riots began Dec. 8 in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. Two Israelis, Ms. <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> and a soldier, have also died. The army said Monday that 4,800 Palestinians have been arrested since the riots began. Five hundred of them have been convicted, 3,400 are awaiting trial and 900 are being held in administrative detention, which allows imprisonment without trial for six months. Arab residents of the occupied territories followed <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> orders to close stores and stay home from jobs in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on Monday. Underground leaflets called for a `` day of firebombs'' April 21. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said: `` We strongly oppose deportations from the occupied territories,'' which he described as `` counterproductive. ... They only further inflame passions.'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the practice violates international human rights agreements to which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is a signatory. The Geneva Convention bars expulsion of civilians in time of war, but Israeli officials say the convention applies only to mass expulsions. Army helicopters flew the eight deportees to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s self-proclaimed security zone in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> The army offered them a medical examination and gave each $ 50 before soldiers led them to two taxis heading for Syrian-controlled territory. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television showed some of the men carrying their belongings in plastic bags. When the taxis sped off, one of the Palestinians flashed a victory sign. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio: `` We are not expelling residents. We are only expelling agitators, preachers -LRB- of violence -RRB- and extremists. The past has proven that expulsions are one of the most effective deterrents.'' Palestinian leaders said the expulsions would feed bitterness. `` The more the government uses drastic measures, the more people become determined, even though they do n't have the power to overthrow the authorities,'' said <PERSON> Rashad </PERSON> <PERSON> al </PERSON> <PERSON> Shawwa </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> mayor deposed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Monday's deportation was the second in four months of riots. The expulsion of four Palestinians on Jan. 13 provoked an international outcry. More than 1,000 Arabs have been expelled from the territories since 1967. Expulsion orders against five of those expelled Monday were issued three months ago. The most prominent deportee is <PERSON> Abed </PERSON> <PERSON> al </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> Uda </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafia </PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, described by the army as chief ideologue of a Moslem fundamentalist group pledged to destroy <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and create a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> homeland through war. <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Freij </PERSON>, a Christian Palestinian who is mayor of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, called the deportations `` a revenge for <PERSON> Beita </PERSON>,'' the village where <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> attacked 16 teen-age hikers and two armed guards from <ORGANIZATION> Elo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moreh </ORGANIZATION>, a Jewish settlement. `` It was done to appease the settlers,'' <PERSON> Freij </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Uri </PERSON> <PERSON> Ariel </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlements council, said Monday's action was `` too little too late'' and demanded more expulsions. The <PERSON> Beita </PERSON> clash Wednesday has provoked debate along party lines since army investigators said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> apparently was struck by a bullet from the gun of <PERSON> Romem </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubi </PERSON>, one of the two guards accompanying the teen-agers. Settlers and right-wing legislators said the army report was one-sided. <PERSON> Geulah </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> of the right-wing party <ORGANIZATION> Tehiya </ORGANIZATION> said Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>, the army chief of staff, `` jumped to conclusions and, acting as a judge, pointed an accusing finger at the settlers.'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, who leads the center-left <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said to the critics: `` This is very serious, the attempt to involve the army in political matters.''
