<FIRST>r a AM-TestBan     04-11 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Test Ban,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Hail Limited Test Ban Treaty to Mark 25th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials marked the 25th anniversary of the Limited Test Ban Treaty Monday by hailing it as a historic pact that laid the groundwork for subsequent nuclear arms agreements. Officials gathered at the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> and Museum to reminisce about the events surrounding its signing. Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubinin </PERSON> praised President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who oversaw the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side of negotiations, saying the treaty `` would not have been attained without a fresh and sober look'' at superpower rivalry by `` that dynamic leader.'' Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, brother of the late president, called the treaty a `` watershed event in Soviet-American relations ... the first major arms control agreement involving the superpowers.'' The treaty, signed July 25, 1963, after 10 days of negotiations in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> involving Soviet, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> representatives, banned testing of nuclear weapons in the atmosphere, in outer space and under water. Other testing bans have been signed since, but the Test Ban Treaty remains the only one ratified by both superpowers. Former Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participants in the negotiations agreed at a news conference that the treaty gave rise to a series of other nuclear arms pacts between the superpowers, including last year's accord to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear weapons <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Bundy </PERSON>, special assistant for national security affairs from 1961 to 1966, told reporters the signing `` brought a prospect of further and larger agreements,'' and praised <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> for ignoring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> perceptions that the Soviets were further advanced in testing. <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Roshchkin </PERSON>, a disarmament expert in the Soviet foreign ministry at the time of the signing, concurred. `` This was a first step in post-war history ... a first step in the field of disarmamanent,'' he said. <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorensen </PERSON>, special counsel to the president from 1961 to 1963 and part of a small group of advisers that guided the talks from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by telephone, said `` there was a great sense of joy and relief when word was received'' at the White House that the treaty had been signed. `` But backslapping was not the Kennedy way,'' <PERSON> Sorensen </PERSON> said. `` On the contrary, he immediately began to worry about <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratification,'' which came in the fall. Intense lobbying by the president left only 11 Democrats and eight Republicans opposed. Soviet officials recalled the jubilation of their leader, <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, as described by former <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in his book, `` A Thousand Days.'' As <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Undersecretary of State <PERSON> Averell </PERSON> <PERSON> Harriman </PERSON> strode through a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> park, `` a huge crowd collected behind them,'' <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> wrote. According to the book, <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> turned and asked the crowd: `` ` We've just signed a test-ban treaty. I'm going to take him to dinner. Do you think he's earned his dinner?' The people applauded and applauded.'' The signing and subsequent ratification followed 336 nuclear explosions in the atmosphere by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> over 13 years. The agreement also was important as a tangible sign of emerging detente after the Cuban missile crisis of October 1962 brought the world to the brink of nuclear war. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the only other nations that openly engaged in nuclear weapons test programs, have not agreed to the test ban. But all <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> nuclear explosions have been underground since 1974, and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> exploded its last atmospheric device in 1980. Disagreement on verification measures has held up joint ratification of the 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty and the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty limiting test explosions to 150 kilotons. A kiloton equals the explosive force of 1,000 tons of TNT. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators began a second round of talks on ratifying those two treaties in February, and participants Monday invoked the Limited Test Ban treaty as an example that agreement is possible.
</TEXT>
