re is a difference in seeing a weapon in the hands of a police officer and seeing a weapon in the hands of a thug,'' <PERSON> Driver </PERSON> told defense attorney <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> objected to much of Driver's testimony, claiming it was hearsay. Driver has been allowed to sit through the testimony of all witnesses in the trial. When members of <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s smuggling group were indicted in 1981, <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> was listed as one of the co-defendants. Driver testified that federal officials spent four days in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> meeting with the attorney general of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> in 1983 to seek <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s extration to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. On the trip were <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> and another <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent, <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Starratt </PERSON>. As a result of that visit, an extradition order was signed in May 1984. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> was not arrested until Feb. 4, 1987. Driver also testified about the arrest in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> of <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s smuggling group, and said that on their flight back to <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> about a DC-3 the group began singing `` Homeward Bound'' and commercial jingles The jury also was shown a videotape taken last April on a visit to <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay by <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> and Driver that showed the island had become nearly deserted. Introduced into evidence Monday were address and telephone books confiscated in a raid on <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s house in February 1987. The books contained phone numbers for <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, plus t