<HEAD>Hijackers of Kuwaiti Jet May Have Smuggled Weapons Through Service
Ramp</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The weapons aboard a hijacked Kuwaiti airliner may have been smuggled aboard in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> through the ramp area used by caterers and cleaning crews, an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> official said Monday. `` On the basis of discussions we've had so far, the probability is weapons were placed on board the aircraft through the coercion or collusion of staff on the ramp,'' said <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON>, head of security for the association. Caterers, engineers, cleaners and loaders all have access to the ramp area where the cabin of the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 was serviced and cleaned before it left <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on Tuesday, he said. Thai authorities have not completed their investigation, he added. There are believed to be at least five Arab hijackers on board the jumbo jet, which was commandeered Tuesday on its way to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and has been sitting on the tarmac in <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, since Friday. The hijackers have killed two passengers and threatened to kill the remaining passengers if authorities do not fulfill their demand that the plane be refueled. About 45 hostages are being held. <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said he thought the weapons were placed on board through the ramp area because it is highly unlikely five people could take guns and grenades through security gates at <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> airport. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> is a Montreal-based international association of commercial airlines. `` The initial reaction of the Thais was, ` it could n't have happ