ublished Monday. Asked if his departure from the country would end the crisis and alleviate the suffering of Panamanians, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> said: `` If the people are suffering, it is because of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, not me.'' <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s crisis began when <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> depose President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> on Feb. 26, the day after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire the general. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still considers <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> the legal head of state. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is under federal indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, which he denies. In <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, a Panamanian opposition leader forced into exile said <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> will start running out of basic foodstuffs in days and such a shortage could lead to the `` final push'' to remove <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Lastra </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> Sunday night from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after 11 days in prison. He was imprisoned after leading a protest march and said authorities told him he could either remain in jail or go into exile. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> urged Latin American nations to abandon their opposition to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic pressures designed to remove <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` We have been successful in that in ten months we have taken away all <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s support without shedding blood. What he needs now is a final push, and this could be when the economic situation grows sharply worse in the next few weeks, basically for a lack of food,'' he said.
