<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON>, an author, teacher and critic of the medical establishment, is dead at age 61. <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON>, who died April 5 at his home in <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION> after a brief illness, wrote the books `` Confessions of a Medical Heretic,'' published in 1979, and `` How to Raise a Healthy Child In Spite of Your Doctor,'' published in 1984. <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON> also wrote a syndicated newspaper column, ` The People's Doctor.'' `` He was probably the nation's most vocal critic of organized medicine,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bradley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Method </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Childbirth </ORGANIZATION>, a California-based group on whose advisory board <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON> served. `` He served as a kind of catalyst for many different organizations'' that question medical orthodoxy, <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON> said. `` My favorite quote of his is, ` You should kick the hospital habit at birth.''' <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON> was a professor and instructor of pediatrics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He also taught at <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> medical school. He was a former director of development at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Reese </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON> and a former national director of <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Head </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Start </ORGANIZATION>'s medical consultation service. <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON> is survived by his wife, two daughters and six grandchildren, hi