<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> may further reduce the sentences of three leaders of a Jewish terror group that operated for four years in the occupied territories, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Ami </PERSON> <PERSON> Gluska </PERSON>, said in a written statement that `` all such reports are baseless.'' The radio said the president is considering reducing the sentences of <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Livni </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shaul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharbaf </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jewish </PERSON> settlers who staged a gun and grenade attack at the <ORGANIZATION> Hebron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> that killed three Palestinians and wounded 33 in August 1983. They were sentenced to life in prison in July 1985 but <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> reduced their punishment last year to 24 years each. Several right-wing political leaders have appealed to <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> to pardon the men. The radio said the president was considering a further reduction of their terms in honor of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 40th anniversary. The three settlers were among 25 arrested in 1984 and charged with planning and conducting six attacks against Arabs in the territories captured by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in the 1967 Middle East War. On April 1, <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> ordered the freedom of two other people convicted of taking part in the group's activities. <PERSON> Gluska </PERSON> called the move part of `` a general trend to reduce sentences in the framework of the 40th year of the state.'' One of those freed was New York-born <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>, who was serving a two-year sentence for helping to plant a bomb in the car of then-Nablus Mayor <PERSON> Bassam </PERSON> <PERSON> 