<HEAD>Four Killed In Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three black men were fatally shot and the fourth was stabbed to death in separate attacks near the southeastern coastal city of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>, police said Monday. The killings in the <LOCATION> Hammersdale </LOCATION> area outside <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> were announced in the Monday morning police report which covers incidents during the previous 24 hours. The report gave no additional details on the killings. At least 16 people were injured by guns, knives and fighting when rioting broke out Sunday at an overcrowded black music festival in <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>, police said. Police said they fired shots in an attempt to control the crowd at Kings Park rugby stadium, which seats 50,000. Approximately 120,000 people attended the festival, which began at midday and lasted about six hours despite the scattered violence. Black unrest has declined sharply in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in the past year. The only area reporting regular flare-ups in recent months has been the southeastern city of <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, where about 500 people have died in black factional feuding since the beginning of 1987. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
