<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, referring to <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> as one of the `` most extreme elements'' in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, called Monday on Jewish and <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> to start <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace talks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Talks can, in fact, begin right here in this country,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. His proposal came as the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> presidential primary campaign entered its final week. Nearly one quarter of the Democratic electorate on April 19 will be Jewish and for many of those voters, the future of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is a critical issue. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appeared to be reaching out to Jewish voters on Sunday when he declared that as president he would not meet with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, whom he has been criticized for meeting several years ago. At a breakfast meeting on Monday, he also ridiculed suggestions that he would come under greater scrutiny as a result of the electoral successes that have placed him only a handful of delegates behind Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in the Democratic race. Running third in the three-candidate race was Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the former civil rights activist, said there had been suggestions that the news media and the other candidates would get tough with him. `` Well, get tough,'' he said. `` Who else has a budget for fighting the drug crisis? `` Who else has a budget deficit plan? `` Who else has significant foreign policy experience?'' And then he said, `` I look forward to tougher days.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked about <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> and he said, `` It would not be a good approach to start at the table with the most extreme elements _ that's a formula for catastrophe.'' Instead, he said, `` In this city some of your top Palestinian leaders in the world live. Some of your top <PERSON> Jewish-American </PERSON> and pro-Israeli leaders live. We should begin to talk here, to implore both sides to a higher level of security.'' He brushed aside questions about whether he would meet with the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>, a group <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke to on Monday. He said he also was addressing concerns of Haitians living in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, of people from the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, as well as of <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> and Irish Americans. Later, an aide said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had no room on his schedule to meet with the Jewish group. Monday evening, labor leaders and the rank and file turned out in force at a labor rally in support of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s candidacy. The candidate was interrupted repeatedly with shouts of `` Win, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, Win!'' _ an updated version of the `` Run, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, Run!'' slogan chanted during his unsuccessful first run for president in 1984. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told about 5,000 supporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Jacob </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> K. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Javits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> that blue-collar workers `` will have a friend in the White House'' if he becomes president. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> reminded the crowd, which represented a wide cross-section of the labor movement, that he has stood with them