<HEAD>Taiwan's Geriatric Parliament Set For Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the geriatric world of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, lawmakers have been dying this year at the rate of two a month, and the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has a representative who is 74 The Legislative Yuan, the highest of the three lawmaking branches of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, is populated by scores of octagenarians and nonagenarians elected in 1948 on the Chinese mainland. Many are hospitalized today and can not attend sessions, including 97-year-old <PERSON> Chao </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu-hsu </PERSON>, the senior member. Six members died in the first three months of 1988, lowering to 306 the number of mainland-elected lawmakers still in the 884-seat body at the end of March. The aging lawmakers were part of the <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>'s Nationalist mainland government, which was forced to flee to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> a year later by the victory of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-Tung </PERSON>'s Communists in the civil war <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> died in 1975 at the age of 87, and <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> died in 1976 at 83. The Nationalist leaders on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> still claim to be the rightful rulers of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and have frozen the lawmakers elected in 1948 into office until the government can return to the mainland to hold new elections. Starting in 1969, however, Taiwanese were allowed seats in the legislature. But with native Taiwanese seeking a greater say in today's government and the mainland-elected lawmakers becoming increasingly feeble, the Nationalists are facing calls to take the gray out of the Legislative Yuan `` Over the past 40 years the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- has never paid enough attention to the voice of the people,'' said <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kao-cheng </PERSON>, a lawmaker from the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` The whole constitutional structure is distorted and destroyed.'' In February, the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or Kuomintang, proposed voluntary retirement for the remaining mainland-elected lawmakers and an increase in the number of seats open for election on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, which now stands at 73. The proposal also would apply to the 934-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, the branch that meets every six years to choose <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s president. The other legislative branch is the Control Yuan, which serves as a watchdog. The opposition party has denounced the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> plan, however, arguing that all seats, including those of the mainlanders, should be open for election. In the meantime, <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> and 11 other opposition party members elected in 1986 are making life miserable for the aging lawmakers. Most of the mainland-elected members belong to the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> but some belong to smaller groups, including 74-year-old <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzu-peng </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers constantly refer to the elderly members as `` old thieves.'' They also get into fights with the Nationalists, rip apart furniture and generally cause chaos whenever possible during Legislative Yuan sessions. The 33-year-old <PERSON> Chu </PERSON>'s exploits in this have earned him the nickname `` Rambo'' in the local media. On April 7, <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> stormed the Legislative Yuan podium to stop a vote on the budget. He wound up in a wild melee with several Nationalists that resulted in a decision to provide the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yuan </ORGANIZATION>'s aging president and vice president with bodyguards. The mass-circulation <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said that among those who punched and kicked <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> during the scuffle were several elderly Nationalist lawmakers who `` had suppressed their displeasure for too long.'' Opposition lawmakers recently have taken to the streets to protest the `` 10,000-year Parliament'' and in March led a group of more than 1,000 people to a walled suburban compound where many of the aging Nationalists live. At least 16 people were reported injured when demonstrators clashed with the security forces. Opposition party members also have publicized the telephone numbers of mainland-elected representatives and have urged people to call them to demand they retire. Nationalist lawmaker <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hung-hsueh </PERSON>, 72, said he receives one or two calls late each night. Some callers curse while others remain silent, he said. He added that he receives paper money traditionally offered to the dead with his name on it. `` This is shameful -LRB- and -RRB- mean, but it does not bother me,'' <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> said in a recent interview. He said he always replies to the callers with a polite: `` Thank you. I am still alive.'' <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> believes that holding elections in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> for the entire Legislative Yuan would be unconstitutional on grounds that it would become a local lawmaking body. His belief is shared by other mainland-elected representatives. But reform of the parliamentary system was firmly pushed by President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>'s son who died at the age of 77 in January, as part of his sweeping policy to introduce democratic change to the island. His successor, President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON>, is a firm supporter of the voluntary retirement package and final details are expected to be announced in coming months.
</TEXT>
