<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs April 19 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Libya Swarms with `Guests' _ Including Californian with a Cross</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The writer, who is based in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, recently was a `` guest'' in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and took notes for this story while waiting around, as guests often must do.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A guest in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> _ and there are guests galore _ does a lot of waiting, but there's always the entertainment of watching other guests. Recently there was the man who identified himself as <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Blessit </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. He showed up one day pulling a wooden cross on wheels and said he's been doing that for the past 19 years in all parts of the world. He told a Libyan television crew he and his teen-age son planned to pull the cross from <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> through the desert to <LOCATION> Ghadames </LOCATION>, 250 miles to the south, near the borders of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>. When <PERSON> Blessit </PERSON> and his cross rolled out of sight, <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Weifenbach </PERSON> came by the hotel lobby where other guests were waiting around. Weifenbach is the burly, mustachioed West German who turned to Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> for financing for his ice hockey team back home, and he said he was waiting to catch a plane to <LOCATION> Tobruk </LOCATION>, near the Egyptian border, to hear the <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader make a speech. According to <ORGANIZATION> JANA </ORGANIZATION>, the official Libyan news agency, guests pour into <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> all the time _ from all over, even from Indian reservations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Judging by <ORGANIZATION> JANA </ORGANIZATION>, these `` guests,'' most of them members of official delegations, do n't have a spare moment. They're busy bringing flowers to <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>, busy touring his barracks-home that was damaged in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air attacks in 1986, busy denouncing `` imperialist aggression,'' busy signing guestbooks. Libyan officials like to present guests with `` programs.'' Programs are sometimes a tight schedule of hospital tours, factory visits, maybe even a suddenly arranged late-night chat with `` the leader,'' as <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> is known here. But the programs follow `` Libyan'' time, and `` Libyan'' time means long waits in hotel lobbies and in airport lounges. Some guests, frustrated by the waiting, give up and start for home, only to be yanked back at the plane's door with a promise of an encounter with the `` leader.'' But they eventually find out they've returned only for more waiting at the hotel and looking out over the blue <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. That does n't sound bad; the trouble is, all you can do generally is look, since it's difficult to get out the hotel door. Journalist guests, for example, are often assigned `` assistants.'' These usually are enthusiastic, but sometimes sour-faced young men or women who work for the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. They seem to materialize just when the guest is about to slip out the door for a look around. `` Oh, you know, there might be a press conference with the leader,'' my assistant tells me. `` Maybe an interview. Maybe very soon.'' The guest sinks into a lobby sofa and orders another soft drink or tea; alcohol is forbidden in <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s revolutionary Islamic society. For a change of pace from lounge lounging, there is corridor pacing. Many of the pacers in hotel corridors are proponents of various causes and countries, looking for a sympathetic ear. Visitors sometimes feel like they're in a spy movie, with guests approaching each other stealthily, whispering messages to each other. An Arab man leaned toward a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> woman in the hotel restaurant and said: `` I have something important to tell you.'' `` Yes?'' `` You have nice legs.'' One sunny afternoon, four Western visitors asked their assistants for a car to go to <LOCATION> Sabratha </LOCATION>, site of an ancient Greco-Roman theater, 45 miles west of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. Yes, maybe, there was a car, but it was broken. It might be fixed but not for several hours, and the ruins close at sunset. The guests turned to the taxi drivers outside. Sure, said one. `` Fifteen dinars'' -LRB- about $ 50 -RRB-. The Libyan assistants appeared and said something quietly in Arabic to the driver. `` Thirty dinars. Maybe 50,'' said the driver. It was clear the assistants did n't want the guests going off without a program. A few days later, <ORGANIZATION> JANA </ORGANIZATION> reported on the doings of an Austrian youth delegation. The youths went to a poultry factory and to the ruins of <LOCATION> Sabratha </LOCATION>, it said. They had a program.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs April 19</NOTE>
