<HEAD>adv15</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Family Awaits for Word of Irishman Missing Two Years in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two years after <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> disappeared in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, his mother and two sisters say they too have become hostages to unknown kidnappers. `` If they could only let us know whether he's alive or dead _ even if he's dead, it would be better than hoping all the time,'' said his younger sister, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>. Despite petitions and appeals to the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> people and the Iranian and <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> governments, no group has claimed responsibility for the disappearance of the 37-year-old teacher, who is a citizen of the Irish republic to the south even though he was born and lived in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> rushed out of his apartment April 11, 1986, late for an 8 a.m. lecture at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> where he had taught for four months. His mistake, the family believes, was to forget his Irish passport. They believe he was kidnapped by people who may have thought he was American or British, rather than a citizen of a small neutral country. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s only involvement in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> is through aid groups and its contingent in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Immediately after <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> disappeared, the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> government in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> issued photographs of his passport and repeatedly broadcast that he was an Irish citizen, raising the family's hopes that he might be released quickly. But two years later, <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> remains the only Irishman among the 22 foreigners missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. His family is resigned to an indef