y's held hostage as well,'' she said `` In our own home, you're afraid to go out in case the phone rings. If you go out for a night out, you feel guilty, the fact that you might be trying to enjoy yourselves and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>'s sitting in a cell somewhere.'' Belfast-born <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> had lived in the turmoil of sectarian strife that has gripped <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> for nearly 20 years. A Protestant, he chose to become a citizen of predominantly <LOCATION> Roman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Catholic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> rather than of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which governs the province. Everyone born in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> has the option of becoming a citizen of either. In addition to teaching, <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> was a community worker for the <ORGANIZATION> Belfast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` He has many Protestant and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> friends,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Gillham </PERSON>. `` He tried to build communication on both sides. He loved his country.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said the family did not want his kidnapping to become a political issue. In December, two senior officials from <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, the legal political wing of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, went to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> without the family's knowledge to try to win <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON>'s freedom Mrs. <PERSON> Gillham </PERSON> said it was the similarities between <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> that attracted her bearded, easy-going brother to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` When he told me he was going, I said to him, ` Are you sure you know what you're doing? It's like going from the frying pan into the fire.' `` But as <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> said, there's a war there. There's a war here at home and life has to go on.''
