<HEAD>West Germany Says Communist Spies Still Flocking In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even though East-West relations have thawed, communist espionage is on the rise in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and probably is aimed more at high-tech industrial secrets than military or political ones, officials say. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has been infested with communist spies since its creation in 1949 in the ashes of World War II. The spying has ranged from East German truck drivers rolling through the countryside to moles in the highest of government offices. Among the most important spies caught were <PERSON> Guenter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON>, who wrecked Chancellor <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>'s government in 1974; <PERSON> Margret </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeke </PERSON>, who was a secretary to five presidents; and <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotsch </PERSON>, who delivered top-secret <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> documents to the Soviets. But just last month, West German federal police arrested 11 people suspected of working for the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>, the Soviet intelligence agency, and are investigating others. `` The large number of arrests confirms that instead of refraining from activating agents in a time of detente, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc is intensifying its espionage activities,'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> told reporters after the March sweep. <PERSON> Hans-Gert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>, spokesman for the Office for the Protection of the Constitution, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s counter-espionage agency, said warmer East-West relations increase the opportunities for spying. `` The thaw has increased interest in obtaining information, and also improved conditions for espionage,'' <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> said in an interview at his <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION> office. <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> added that because some communist countries have loosened emigration restrictions, a danger increases that agents have been planted among the refugees. `` Emigration plays an important role in espionage in the Federal Republic -LRB- <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB-, as has been shown by the arrest of the suspected <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents,'' <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> said. Among the 11 suspects arrested in March were four Soviet emigres. With communist research lagging behind the West in many areas, Soviet bloc agents have intensified their efforts to obtain secrets from private companies in science and high-tech fields, <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> said. `` The interest in political secrets is still great, but for technological and scientific matters it has grown considerably,'' <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> said. Security officials estimate that as many as 3,000 spies are at work in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, most of them from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Between 30 and 50 suspected spies are arrested each year, the counter-intelligence office says. Secretaries and other government employees in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, the nation's capital, are among those who have been caught Also, security officials have long suspected that East German truckers driving through <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> report on military movements and gather other information for the East German secret service. But a spy can come from anywhere. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> automatically grants citizenship to all ethnic German refugees from the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc, making the task of isolating communist agents extremely difficult. In addition, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have improved relations over the past few years, resulting in more contacts between the two sides and greater chances for espionage. East German authorities have allowed the resettling of its citizens to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to increase dramatically, reaching a high of 30,000 in 1984, compared to just 7,000 the year before, according to federal statistics. Past spy scandals have damaged the nation's image among other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> arrested 16 communist agents in 1976 after cracking East German infiltration methods. But it turned out that two of the spies, <PERSON> Lothar-Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutze </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Renate </PERSON>, had been passing <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> documents to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since the 1960s. West German Defense Minister <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Leber </PERSON> resigned over that scandal. In 1974, <PERSON> Guenter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON>, a close aide to Chancellor <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, was exposed as an East German agent, and <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON> resigned. <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> began serving a 13-year jail sentence in 1975 _ the longest ever given by a West German court to a convicted spy _ but he was released six years later in an exchange of agents with <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Constititution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> itself was rocked by the defection to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> of <PERSON> Hans-Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiedge </PERSON>, who headed an agency group responsible for catching East German spies. Security officials believe many of the communist agents in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> now can do only minor damage. `` But one must be careful when one uses the term ` small fish','' said <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>. `` A small fish can always become a bigger one.''
</TEXT>
