<HEAD> EDITOR'S NOTE _ Five years ago, the National Commission on</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Excellence in Education set off alarms with a provocative report that warned of `` a rising tide of mediocrity'' in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools. The man behind that report, <PERSON> Terrel </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, says he never expected such a stir. But now he fears the school reform movement has left behind the bottom 30 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children _ the poor, the minorities, the dropouts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 T.H. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, considered by many to be the father of the school reform movement, views himself as a failure when it came to educating the most important pupil he ever faced: <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Three years after he quit the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Cabinet, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> frets that school reform `` did n't do a darn thing'' to solve the problem of dropouts and those who can barely read the words on their high school diplomas. Most are poor; many are minorities. `` We're losing 30 percent to 40 percent of the rising generation,'' says the former Secretary of Education. `` They're out of school and they're unemployed and unemployable.'' It might have been different, he says, if President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had taken to heart the message of the bombshell report that <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> commissioned, `` A Nation At Risk.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Excellence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> made headlines on April 26, 1983, with its blunt warning: `` The educational foundations of our society are presently being eroded by a rising ride of mediocrity that threatens our very future as a nation and a people.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> responded by extolling tuition tax credits and prayer in public schools _ two things that `` A Nation A Risk'' never touched upon. But the president and his advisers soon realized that it made political sense to pay more attention to education. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> began visiting schools and speaking out about the need for tougher standards for students and teachers alike. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, who had come to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to preside over a department <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had promised to abolish, began traveling with the president on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One and handing out `` flags of excellence'' to schools at White House ceremonies. Governors and business leaders took the school reform message to heart and began pouring more dollars into local school budgets while seeking to hold educators more accountable. <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> `` the second-most important man in this administration.'' And, in perhaps the ultimate compliment, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who had sought to cut billions from the education budget, actually proposed a modest budget increase in 1984, an election year. But when that election was over, <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sent word that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would try with renewed vigor to boot education out of his Cabinet. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> submitted his resignation and returned to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to teach at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>. Now he has written a book, `` The Thirteenth Man: A <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Cabinet Memoir,'' that lays bare his struggles within the administration and the regrets that set in after he left it. `` I tried to convince the president and his people of the bonds that tie together education, the economy and military strength. But notwithstanding the fact that I had been a teacher for much of my adult life, I never succeeded in getting this lesson across to them,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, in his book, made no mention of his successor, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who has been a forceful advocate of tougher standards for schools and colleges, and has made his own headlines with studies comparing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese schools and proposing a core high school curriculum. But <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> thinks the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration reponse in the second term has been inadequate. `` <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has very effectively used the bully pulpit,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said in an interview. `` But for some reason the response has n't been such as to rally the whole nation around this _ the fact that we're losing a third of the whole nation to academic deficiency and illiteracy I'm not talking about <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> so much as I am about <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.'' `` We missed an opportunity to fully take advantage of ` A Nation At Risk' and all the attention on it by not giving it a high priority and a high profile in the second term,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> says. `` Had the president done that, the results of the reform movement would have been much more impressive than they are.'' <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> credits <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> with moving the country `` away from the drift toward the welfare state and highlighting the strength of our capitalist, free enterprise system.'' But, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> adds, `` He could have added to that by being the president who turned around and solved the American education system. We ca n't say that now.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, asked about the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> book at a congressional hearing, said `` The Thirteenth Man'' suggests <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> was the `` only virtuous man in the administration and the rest were knaves and louts.'' `` Unlike Bell, I wo n't leave the job and then go write a book criticizing the people for whom I worked,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
