<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: Bennett said.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> takes no comfort from the education rhetoric he has heard from the presidential candidates, including promises from both <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that they will be `` the education president.'' `` We should be asking the presidential candidates: ` If elected, what do you plan to do to lead the nation into a truly great education system and to transform <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> into a learning society?''' Even before it was published, `` The Thirteenth Man'' made headlines with <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s claim that he heard `` mid-level right-wing staffers in the White House and at <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>'' make racist jokes and ethnic slurs. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> has never named names. The book recounts <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s bitter, often losing struggles within the administration on budget, personnel and policy with people whom he regarded as conservative ideologues. Conservatives regarded <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> as a mole of the education establishment in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Cabinet, a big-spending liberal who had testified in 1978 in favor of creating the Education Department. If they needed any evidence to support those views, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> provides it in abundance in `` The Thirteenth Man.'' `` Those who accused me of being part of the educational establishment were right,'' said <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, who had served two previous stints in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, one as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commissioner of education in the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> administration, between school posts in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. Bell calls for $ 25 billion in new federal, state and local spending on the Chapter 1 remedial program for disadvantaged students, Head Start, the pre-school program for poor children, and the Job Corps. He said the country should attack the problems of illiteracy and dropouts with `` a national movement of the magnitude of the Marshall Plan that helped rebuild the war-ravaged nations of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at the end of World War II.'' But, he says, `` money by itself is not the answer. We can not ignore the other part of education, and that's the home and family.'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s own life story is testimony to the power of both education and the family. Bell grew up in poverty in <LOCATION> Lava </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. His father died in an accident in 1929 when <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> was 8. His mother, <PERSON> Alta </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, raised nine kids in the Depression on virtually no money. When he graduated from high school as valedictorian he wore a suit that, without his knowledge, Mrs. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> had bought with money donated by his teachers. He headed off to the college with the lowest tuition in the state, <ORGANIZATION> Albion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Normal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. It charged $ 11.50 per semester. `` My life at <LOCATION> Albion </LOCATION> opened richnesses beyond anything I ever imagined,'' he recalls. `` I was ignorant of our own history and of the great literature of the Western world. I knew nothing of the Federalist Papers, the works of Tolstoy, or the rudiments of economics. This all came to me courtesy of the taxpayers who founded and supported a state normal school to prepare teachers to teach their children and grandchildren.'' It also came courtesy of President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s New Deal and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which supported the part-time <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> job that paid him $ 17 a month _ enough to cover his $ 4 rent and leave $ 13 for food, which his mother supplemented by mailing four loaves of bread every Wednesday. His experiences at <LOCATION> Albion </LOCATION>, now defunct, made it all the harder for <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> to support <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> cuts in student aid, cuts he now says were `` absolutely wrong.'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said that when he left <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to return to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, `` I had a nagging feeling of betrayal.. I felt frustration at not having been able to secure an enduring commitment to the cause of education at the highest federal level. On the positive side, he says, `` we are educating 60 to 70 percent of the youth of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> better than in previous decades.'' College-entrance test scores have stopped sliding, states have raised high school graduation requirements dramatically and installed competency tests for both students and entry-level teachers, and `` at least 30 states have taken steps to build career ladders for teachers that reward distinguished teaching performance.'' But, he says, then there are the bottom 30 percent to 40 percent of students for whom the push for school reform `` did n't do a darn thing.'' `` In my mind,'' he adds, `` nothing could have assured <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s place in history more than his enduring commitment to the school reform movement that he supported so effectively for 18 months, only to abandon it after the election.'' `` Failure to educate millions of our people adequately will move us toward disaster if we do not alter course,'' he warns.
</TEXT>
