<HEAD>French Election: `What Will Change, Whoever Wins?'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LE FORNET, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From the crumbling manor he shares with his sheep, <PERSON> Adolphe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonnevie </PERSON> frowns into his field glasses at a <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> caught between star wars and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> XIV. He is not cheered by the presidential campaign around him. `` What will change, whoever wins?'' he asked, expressing a common view of the likely re-election of <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. `` What changed in the last seven years? More unemployment, the same problems.'' In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, lawyer <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilliaert </PERSON> made a similar point: `` People believed in ideologies in 1981. They elected <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> as a Socialist, to bring about change. Now they see their problems are beyond ideology. They'll vote for a person, not a party.'' Across <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, people echo <PERSON> Bonnevie </PERSON>'s concerns over jobs, technological competition, agriculture, education and urban problems. Few are willing to express more than guarded optimism. Unemployment is 10.5 percent. Last year's trade deficit of $ 5.5 billion was 60 times higher than in 1986. Economic growth of 2 percent lags far behind <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s. But more, Frenchmen see an erosion of culture and a breaking down of the fabled art of living that once set <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> apart. Old roots are dying, and new growth is too sparse. Around villages like <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Fornet </PERSON>, tucked away in a back corner of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION>, the `` crisis'' takes tangible shape. <PERSON> Bonnevie </PERSON>, an aging farmer, owns most of the village, old stone buildings, cobblestones and a patchwork of fields. He sits in the sun and trains his binoculars on passersby. Most are in ski clothes. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Fornet </PERSON> is three miles from Val d'Isere, which in preparing for the 1992 Winter Olympics, has hurtled itself into the space age. A sleek train rockets skiers straight through the mountain, to the top of <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Daille </PERSON>. <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Isere </PERSON>'s relaxed little main plaza has vanished below a gigantic hotel-mall. The last remnants of the past, a stone home built in 1642, a generation before <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIV </PERSON>, the Sun King, are hardly visible amid a forest of garish signs. `` This is a ski factory,'' grumbles <PERSON> Jean-Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamy </PERSON>, who sold his <ORGANIZATION> Squaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> and is moving to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` They have lost all the flavor, the old way of life, and they'll never get it back.'' In <LOCATION> Albertville </LOCATION>, headquarters of 1992 Winter Olympics, old regulars still shuffle into the Cafe des 4 Vallees and wait, without a word, for <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> to bring their `` petit blanc,'' their glass of wine. But the cafe, redone in plastic and formica, no longer serves <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s hallowed melted ham and cheese sandwich, the croque monsieur. Now there is a goopy microwaved substitute called Love-Croquy, sold along with `` les Love Double Cheeseburger.'' On Easter Sunday, the baker lady was selling brioches at Au Peche Mignon. `` <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, someone else, what's the difference?'' she said, with a merry laugh. `` I'm still working every weekend.'' Down the mountain in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, the heart of old-style <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, a conflict of ages is evident in the modern new neighborhood called <LOCATION> Part </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dieu </LOCATION>, which translates roughly to `` God's Little Acre.'' Futuristic trains cut the old time in half, to two hours, from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>'s high-tech Part Dieu Station. But the <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> car-rental office closes four hours for Sunday lunch. The huge Mr. Chef cafeteria advertises, `` Open 11 a.m. to 9 p.m., even Sundays,'' but it closes for lunch, at 2:30 p.m. Campaign posters cover every flat surface of Part Dieu, but few people questioned in the street say they think any of the candidates can make headway against underlying problems. Most pictures show the jovial face of <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>'s favorite son, who warns that any serious economic recovery will take at least two years of job retraining His rival conservative for the chance to run against <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the May 8 runoff is Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who argues roughly the same thing with a flashier style. Posters also tout arch-conservative <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, who argues foreign cultural pollution is taking <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> from the French. As a dark horse, his ads call him: `` L'Outsider.'' `` It makes no difference,'' said <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Duranson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> driver who prefers sports to politics. `` All of them want the same thing.'' He patted his wallet pocket. `` They clean up, and then they go.''
</TEXT>
