<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LE FORNET: they go.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A malaise was reflected in l'Express magazine. A poll indicated 54 percent of a sample of the nation's elite thought <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was in decline. The country is finding it costly to retain the grandeur of <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>'s defiant defense and foreign policies. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is quietly moving closer to the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Recently, 1,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines from the 6th Fleet came ashore for a two-week exercise, the first on French soil since 1966. Economically, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is to blend into a unified European system by 1992. `` Our motherland is <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, but our future is <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> put it. Less easily defined signs indicate a concern that traditional French values and tastes are at risk. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s main plank is to send home immigrants, fueling racism among those who worry that 2 million people of North African extraction will curdle the melting pot. Ironically, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s far-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has taken votes from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, replacing the old left as the place for disgruntled workers to register their protest. Even dyed-in-the-wool <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> supporters expect their candidate to poll less than 7 percent, half of their 1981 showing and less than a third of their high-water mark after World War II. More generally, middle class French parents worry that youths are growing up selfish, without depth or respect for traditions. Few see campaign programs that might counter the trend. For a large number, it is a cultural vacuum, especially on television. The two private channels licensed last year, amid great hoopla, show only 24.5 percent original French programing. One offering is Sexy Clips, in which nude couples stress togetherness in ways outlawed in some American states. On `` La Roue de la Fortune,'' a perky Frenchwoman turns letters for contestants who spin a giant wheel to decipher a blanked out message. In French, the show's name means, `` The Wheel of Fortune.'' There is also, `` <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prix </ORGANIZATION>'' _ `` The Price is Right.'' Both French productions are licensed by the shows they copy. At 8 a.m., viewers choose among Daffy Duck, <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Panda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>. The pay channel, Canal Plus, retransmits the CBS Evening News in English at that time, and it is fast gaining popularity. Some Frenchmen worry that much of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is falling into foreign hands. Foreigners bought up $ 1 billion worth of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> real estate last year, a fifth of the market. Japanese investors built an office complex at <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION> where once <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> could barely afford a cup of coffee. Most important, people are caught in the middle as the country meshes with the modern world, but old ways foul the gears. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> has made it clear that in a second term, he would set aside Socialist dogma in favor of letting <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> find its own pace. He told an interviewer: `` The country is headed toward a free-market economy, and so let's play it to the hilt. Let us have no half measures.'' But now there is `` OPA,'' an acronym, meaning corporate takeover, that is a new French fad word. When <ORGANIZATION> Schneider </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, a diversified holding company, tried to take over the industrial automation group <ORGANIZATION> Telemecanique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrique </ORGANIZATION>, however, workers blocked it by marching in the streets _ the way <LOCATION> Frenchmen </LOCATION> have done since the Revolution that broke the Sun King's line
</TEXT>
