<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Beetlejuice''; ``The Seventh Sign''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Beetlejuice'' Sometimes a devilishly dynamic performance lifts a movie out of the ordinary. That happened last year with <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON>'s satanic furioso in `` The Witches of Eastwick.'' Now comes <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> in the title role of `` Beetlejuice.'' <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> outroars a banshee. His head rotates with a velocity of which <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> never dreamed. He is so unspeakably, devotedly evil that he becomes almost lovable. It's a great comic performance that redeems the obvious crowd-grabbing strategy behind `` Beetlejuice.'' Curiously, the movie begins much the same as `` The Witches of Eastwick.'' The camera hovers over a picture-postcard <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> village and travels through the immaculate streets and freshly painted buildings to focus on a hilltop house that looks a bit huge for its surroundings. The occupants are a pair of cheerful yuppies, <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geena </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, whose main occupation appears to be puttering around the mammoth house. Their work is interrupted when they drive into town for supplies. On the return they swerve on a covered bridge, land in the river and drown. Rather confusedly, they return to the house as ghosts slightly less sophisticated than <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> and <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> in `` Topper.'' Their lives continue much the the same, though invisibly, until the house is sold to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. He moves in with his death-obsessed daughter, <PERSON> Winona </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryder </PERSON>, and his second wife, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>, who is hellbent to transform the house into a chic monstrosity. Alarmed by what is happening to their house, the yuppies seek help from the after-life bureaucracy, a useless exercise. Finally, they enlist the infamous <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> who rises from his grave to perpetrate his monstrous deeds. Director <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> -LRB- `` Pee-Wee's Big Adventure'' -RRB- is a former <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> animator, and his film has the kinetic energy of a cartoon. There is also a synthetic plot, credited to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaaren </PERSON>, which affords little of the logic needed for a convincing fantasy. Unrecognizable in his weirdo makeup, <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> behaves outrageously; it's a marvelous characterization. Also helpful are <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> -LRB- `` Ferris Beuller's Day Off'' -RRB-, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON> -LRB- `` SCTV'' -RRB- and <PERSON> Winona </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryder </PERSON> as the invaders. `` Beetlejuice'' was produced by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashimoto </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> release is rated PG, mostly for its scare quotient. Running time: 92 minutes. _ By <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Seventh Sign'' An intense man walks purposely through the sands of a beach in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. He stares ponderously at the sea, breaks a small, round token and tosses it and a piece of parchment into the water. Almost immediately, sea life washes up _ dead. This purportedly foretells the coming of the apocalypse _ the ultimate destruction of evil and triumph of good. It is the first of seven signs, and in the <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> movie, `` The Seventh Sign,'' only one woman can stop it. The woman is <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>? <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> of the Brat Pack? <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> who is also Mrs. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> -LRB- `` Moonlighting'' -RRB- <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>? <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> who is about as compelling on screen as Gumby? What in the name of <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Karloff </PERSON> is she doing in a `` serious'' occult thriller? However, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s tepid performance in the Tri-Star Pictures release is only one problem with this meandering and misguided movie. One by one, the signs happen: A village is frozen in the middle of the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> desert; a river runs with blood; hail the size of a baseball falls in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>; there's an unexpected eclipse in which the moon becomes red. Interestingly enough, no one in the news media, science or government takes any notice. The stranger -LRB- <PERSON> Jurgen </PERSON> <PERSON> Prochnow </PERSON> -RRB- rents a room from <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, who are played by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Biehn </PERSON>, who limps through his role, and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Abby </PERSON>, who is seven months pregnant, discovers more tokens and parchments in his room and takes one of the pages to a rabbi for translation. But she offends him and instead gets assistance from the scholar's brash young neighbor, <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> -RRB-, who not only tells her that she's up to her agnostic chin in the apocalypse but also becomes her sidekick. Meanwhile, hot on the heels of the <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>'s boarder is a priest named <PERSON> Lucci </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> -RRB- who is investigating the strange signs for the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. Is he good or evil? If you can sit through another 20 minutes of the movie, you'll find out. While <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> tries to figure out how to stop the apocalypse, her lawyer husband tries to save his client, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON>, from the gas chamber. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a 20-year-old who has Down's Syndrome, gives an excellent and sensitive performance as the tormented <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON>, who killed his mother and father in God's name because they were brother and sister _ incest was against the way of God. <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> has constant flashbacks to another time in history: little flickers of a centurion; a tortured man of goodness; a woman holding a water vessel. It's easy to figure out who is who and what is what, especially since the movie was released during the Easter-Passover season. What's not easy to figure out is why the filmmakers did n't pay more attention to organization and sense in their production, and plug in the many holes that make `` The Seventh Sign'' the eighth wonder of muddled movies. The <ORGANIZATION> Interscope </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION>, with a script by <PERSON> W.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wicket </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, is saved only by the lovely and