<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Birth, School, Work, Death'' -LRB- Epic -RRB- _ The Godfathers For a while there, it seemed like bands from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had forgotten how to rock and roll. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s island lately has produced an overabundance of frothing pop and synthesizer-drenched angst. Now along come the Godfathers, with a sound as vaguely sinister as their name. The Godfathers combine classic 1960s rock song structures with the aggressive cynicism of punk. Frankly, they'd be lost in the crowd if placed in either of those two eras, but the current lack of energy makes the Godfathers stand out. The title track of `` Birth, School, Work, Death,'' performed with a sneer by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyne </PERSON>, puts the `` life stinks, then you die'' bumper-sticker philosophy to music. In the process, it sums up the working-class frustrations that course through the Godfathers' music Unfortunately, cliches litter their writing, and nowhere is it more evident than here. Far better is `` If I Only Had Time,'' with a melody that leaves a more lasting impression than the chanted chorus of the title cut. `` If I only had time,'' <PERSON> Coyne </PERSON> sings, `` I'd think of the perfect crime. Guitarists <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kris </PERSON> <PERSON> Dollimore </PERSON> shine with a sloppy exuberance, leading one to believe their own personal godfather is <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>. They're at their best in the rockabilly `` S.T.B.,'' and the droning lead guitar salvages the silly psychedelia of `` When Am I Coming Down?'' In sound and stance, the Godfathers could be British cousins to the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Satellites, minus the sense of humor. Their youthful energy wins them more respect than their songs at this point, but the Godfathers are worth keeping an eye on.
