<HEAD>Anti-Smoking Group To Ask Airline Stockholders For Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national anti-smoking group says it plans to ask shareholders of major airlines to do what it says the federal government has not done: enact a total ban on smoking during all domestic flights. <PERSON> Ahron </PERSON> <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smoke </ORGANIZATION>, said in a weekend interview the group will attempt to arrange shareholder votes at major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines over the issue. <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON> said the new federal law that will ban smoking on domestic airline flights of two hours or less beginning April 23 is a good first step but contains loopholes. Because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> used a time limit rather than mileage, airline flights scheduled for just under two hours could escape compliance, he said. Flight time can be altered by the rate of climb, flight altitude, the type of aircraft being used, headwinds and the schedule of the airports involved, <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON> said. The federal ban on smoking during short-term flights will expire in two years if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> takes no further action, but <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON> does n't expect that to happen. Nevertheless, his Cincinnati-based group does not want to wait for two years to get further action. <PERSON> Leichmtan </PERSON> said the group planned to take the issue to the annual stockholders' meetings of every major airline. In addition to seeking a total smoking ban, the group wants airline executives to designate 50 percent of all flights over two hours as smoke free. The group chose <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> to announce its new strategy because <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, based in the suburb of <LOCATION> Eden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prairie </LOCATION>, already has banned smoking on nearly all of its domestic flights, <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON> said. He said the group planned to go to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and tentatively <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where other major carriers are based to raise questions about the health, safety, economic and legal issues raised by passenger smoking on aircraft, he said. `` We are going to attempt to prove to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> that increased carbon monoxide levels caused by smoking in airplanes puts a flight attendant at risk by reducing the ability to think clearly,'' <PERSON> Leichtman </PERSON> said. He suggested that smokers be provided with nicotine gum or nicotine pills if they could not otherwise physically handle smoke-free flights.
</TEXT>
