 The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market indicator surged to a new closing high today, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar gained ground in trading against the Japanese yen. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected issues, which shed a modest 20.33 points last Friday, gained 175.98 points, or 0.65 percent, finishing the first day of the week at 26,924.87. The Nikkei's close today surpassed the previous high set last Thursday when it closed at 26,768.22. Monday's close was 278.44 points above its pre-crash best level of 26,646,43, set the week before the worldwide stock market crash last October. `` Boosted by the last week's advance on Wall Street, the Nikkei average went up to less than two points short of touching the 27,000-point level,'' said <PERSON> Fumihiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Morimoto </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>. The index reached 26,998.36 points, the highest ever, at one time during the morning trade. Investors spread their buying through most sectors amid bullish sentiment, traders said. The dollar's stability dispelled whatever doubts investors may have had about <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stocks, they said. In the afternoon, however, <PERSON> Morimoto </PERSON> said concerns that the market was rising too high prompted profit-taking, and the selling eased prices a little. Advancing issues outpaced decliners 531 to 351, while 173 issues were unchanged. Popular issues were electricals and precision machineries. Constructions and housing stocks also rose. Insurances and securities were firm. Volume of the first section trade was an estimated 900 million shares, down from 1.5 billion shares last Friday. In the foreign exchange trading, the dollar closed at 125.71 yen, up 0.53 yen from its close of 125.18 yen last week. It had opened the day at 125.80 and traded between