f $ 361 million. The company has a workforce of about 2,500 in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> cited a victory in a related case to bolster his contention that the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> judgment would be overturned on appeal. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> successfully sued in 1982 to block the federal government from providing water to the slurry pipeline project. <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> appealed, but higher courts upheld the decision, including the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in February. `` In view of the unanimous decision of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> ETSI </ORGANIZATION> case,'' <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> said, `` we expect our position to be vindicated.'' The slurry pipeline was proposed to carry a mixture of pulverized coal and water between <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and several southern states. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> had a contract to supply the pipeline with water from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for 50 years, which would have brought $ 9 million a year in revenue to the state. The suit contended <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> and others violated federal antitrust laws in delaying the 1,400-mile, $ 3.8 billion pipeline, which would have crossed railroad tracks. Attorneys for the state produced a document that said <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> was designated to be the lead railroad to fight the project and the water sale. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> argued that it opposed the pipeline, but that there was no conspiracy. The company also contended that the project was financially doomed regardless of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s water contracts. The jury verdict came amid <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION>'s quest to acquire control of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> railroad. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> has asked the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to reject a competing offer from <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
