<HEAD>EEC Launches $2 Billion Hi-Tech Research Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Research ministers of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> on Monday agreed to spend about $ 2 billion over the next five years on research in information technology. The plan, called ESPRIT II, is designed to help European companies to compete against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. An <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> official said the program, which involves 5,500 researchers from 12 <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries, represents about one-third of all European basic research in information technology. The official said ESPRIT research has led to numerous technological achievements, including the development of T800, the most powerful chip on the market. He said the current phase, which is to begin in late summer, will continue to center on microelectronics and information processing. Under EEC rules, the Community contributes 50 percent to the cost of each project, with the rest coming from the member states. For the first time since 1984, when ESPRIT was launchhed, the Community will allow non-member countries, mainly from <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, to participate.
