<HEAD>Jim Gilmore Jr. Races To Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s office looks more like the winner's circle at the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> 500 than corporate headquarters for his $ 200 million-a-year business empire. Visitors have a hard time figuring out the color of the wall paint. Photographs and paintings of race cars and triumphant drivers accepting roses and trophies cover the office walls and line the corridors from floor to ceiling. But <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> is n't in the racing business _ at least not for a profit. Most of <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>'s income is generated by his broadcasting corporation and automobile dealerships. His success in those areas has allowed <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> to pursue his lifelong passion for auto racing, a preoccupation he adopted from his father. In 1973 <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> signed on friend and Indy 500 champion A.J. <PERSON> Foyt </PERSON>, creating the Gilmore-Foyt Racing Team. `` One of the greatest moments in my life was when A.J. won the Indy 500 for the fourth time -LRB- in 1977 -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, 61, a cheerful, gray-haired man whose blue eyes ignite with excitement each time he mentions racing. The feeling is obviously mutual with <PERSON> Foyt </PERSON>. `` I ca n't say enough about <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>. He's stuck by me through thick and thin,'' said <PERSON> Foyt </PERSON>, who 15 years later continues to drive Gilmore-backed cars. Though backing a winner in the Indy 500 was a new experience, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> was already well accustomed to corporate victory. From his grandfather's profitable downtown <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> department store, <ORGANIZATION> Gilmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> has created a diverse business empire with about 1,000 employees. Of his three auto dealerships, the one in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, is consistently among the top four Chevrolet dealerships in the country, selling as many as 21,000 cars each year, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> also recently announced he would become a partner in <PERSON> Foyt </PERSON>'s Chevrolet dealership in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> owns two <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> television stations, WEHT in <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> KODE-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and two <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> radio stations, WLVE in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> WIVY </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>. Then there's all that real estate in downtown <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION>, including several office buildings and parking lots, and the 2,700-acre hog farm in northern <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. And more. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> also owns an insurance company, is director of a <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> plastics manufacturer and sits on the boards of two banks. He is a partner in the parent company of the <ORGANIZATION> Kalamazoo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wings </ORGANIZATION> hockey team and part-owner of their stadium. He also has minority interests in a <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> advertising firm and an automotive engineering company in <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. As if that were n't enough to keep him busy, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> serves on dozens of local, state and national commissions, ranging from the President's Council on Sports and Physical Fitness to the local chamber of commerce The parent company for his holdings, <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gilmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, has had annual revenues as high as $ 300 million. In 1985, <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON> listed <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> as one of the 400 wealthiest Americans, estimating his worth at $ 160 million. `` Forbes was close, but a little on the high side,'' <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> says with a smile. Maybe so, but it's still not bad for a first-year college dropout who started out by mopping floors at the family department store. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> is quick to admit that most of the money he started out with was inherited. After his grandfather died, his grandmother married the founder of <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the pharmaceutical company, merging <ORGANIZATION> Kalamazoo </ORGANIZATION>'s two wealthiest families. But <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>'s workaholic and perfectionist tendencies have allowed him to make the most of his head start. After growing tired of working in the family's department store, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> was elected <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION>'s youngest mayor, a position he held from 1959-61. A diehard Republican, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> remained active in politics for many years, heading five congressional campaigns for former Rep. <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> also made an unsuccessful bid of his own for a congressional seat in 1980, two years after his first wife died of cancer. `` Running was one of the best things I did in my life, although losing did n't feel very good,'' said <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, the father of five grown children and stepfather to his second wife's four children. Though <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> contends he has no plans to get back into the political arena, he may be lured to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, if his good friend of 12 years, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, is elected president in November. `` I think we're good enough friends that there's a good possibility I might be asked to do something -LRB- in a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, the public servant, also believes in continuing his family's tradition of philanthropy. Instead of sharing his profits with the community through a foundation after his death, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> says he believes in `` working on things while we're still alive.'' `` Every night when I get home from work, I put on a sweater and take a walk downtown and I take notes on things that need to be done,'' he said. And he does n't believe in procrastination. For example, when a <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> homeless shelter needed repairs late last year, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> donated $ 30,000 for an immediate renovation. Maybe that's why A.J. <PERSON> Foyt </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> the diamond-studded ring that went with his Indy victory. `` When he gave it to me, he said, ` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>, you may lose everything else, but you wo n't lose this.'''
