 <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it was willing to discuss a takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> if <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> follows through on a suggestion it may raise its $ 4.5 billion bid. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of the British conglomerate B.A.T. Industries, termed the letter `` an encouraging development'' and said it welcomed the chance for negotiation. Farmers, the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer and seventh-biggest property and casualty insurer, opened the door to talks in a letter from <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Denlea </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer. `` I am requesting hereby that you advise us without delay of any higher offer you are prepared to make,'' <PERSON> Denlea </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Denlea </PERSON> offered to share confidential information disclosed to other potential suitors if <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> agrees to confidentiality guidelines. He set a Tuesday deadline for <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>' response. On March 3, <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, Ky.-based <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> launched an unsolicited $ 63-a-share offer for the Los Angeles-based insurer. In a letter Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehey </PERSON> said the company would consider increasing its offer if Farmers management would agree to negotiate. The issue is complicated by a dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> and insurance regulators in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, one of nine states in which Farmers owns insurance companies. A hearing is set for April 20 on a <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s order that <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> stop soliciting proxies in support of a resolution that would require Farmers directors to reconsider their earlier refusal to negotiate <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> law requires regulatory approval of any change of control of an insurer, and defines control partly as holding `` proxies representing 10 percent or more of the voting securities.'' `` We feel that we'll meet all the statutory requirements,'' <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON> said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> B.A.T. </ORGANIZATION>, a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate, has been seeking a foothold in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial services market for some time.
