<HEAD>Shearson Defends Role In Koppers Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> today defended its role in the hostile takeover attempt of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and denounced the `` bizarre allegation'' that <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, rather than a group led by <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, was trying to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>. `` From an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> viewpoint, not only do we think this to be a Shearson transaction and activity in the normal course of its business, but we also view the uproar by some allies of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> as ill-informed, provcative and ill-advised,'' <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, executive vice president of parent company <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He said it was ill-informed because of the `` continued erroneous assertion that that somehow <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, rather than <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>, is trying to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>, which is simply not true and strikes the management of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> as a bizarre allegation.'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> said it was unfair to characterize <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> as having taken an equity position in the takeover attempt. He said <PERSON> Shearon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> was providing advice and bridge financing for the transaction, both `` normal functions'' for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment banks. But <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> construction materials concern, said <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> @ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> `` has dominated and actively guided every aspect of the planning and execution of the <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> takeover attempt since its secret initiation one year ago.'' <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s unsolicited cash tenderpoffer of $ 45 a share on March 3 has since been sweetened to $ 60 per share. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the British materials and construction firm that bears his name, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel, `` I am not a corporate raider.'' <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> said his firm was `` not the sort of organization that seeks to put people out of work, far from it.'' Commenting on <PERSON> Kopper </PERSON>'s refusal to try to negotiate a merger agreement, <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> said, `` It appears to me that you can never know anything aboet an opposing side until you at least can hear their view.''
