<FIRST>r f AM-BetterTV     04-11 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Better TV,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Does Public Want Same Technology The Television Industry Wants?</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 5:45 p.m. EDT; time set by source. A version moving on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American public may be less willing than the television industry believes to embrace a high-resolution TV system with improved picture quality, clearer images and more brilliant color, according to a study released Monday. The results of the study, by the <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, `` contradict the accepted wisdom ... which posits that high definition TV knocks the socks off everyone who sees it.'' The study found that, to most viewers, the differences between conventional TV and high definition TV, called HDTV, are subtle and that screens would have to be two to three times the size of sets found in most American living rooms to have a significant impact. The Japanese have been working on HDTV for nearly 20 years and are moving forward quickly. They plan to give a preview of their system with broadcasts of this summer's <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics to <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sets in about 50 big-city department stores throughout the country. The picture on a standard television set in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is produced by a signal that scans more than 200,000 dots on 525 lines. The Japanese system has 1,125 scanning lines. Of the 613 people who participated in the study, 62 percent said they preferred the quality of HDTV overall. However, `` this indicates that HDTV is not the same kind of revolutionary shift in technology as experienced in the transition to color in the 1950s and 1960s in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said a report on the study written by <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, and released at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> convention here. `` Although engineers and broadcast professionals see the difference immediately and stronly prefer HDTV ... the differences are more subtle to the untrained eye of the mass audience,'' the report said. <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> is the most talked about development at this year's convention, which began Saturday and ends Tuesday Broadcasters are concerned that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research efforts to develop an industry transmission standard for HDTV, still years away in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, may not be moving fast enough to head off a probable Japanese invasion of the new technology. <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> is expected to be introduced by the Japanese to homes in their country in 1990. The Japanese system requires more than the space allocated to TV channels on the electromagnetic spectrum. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the HDTV system called Hi-Vision will be transmitted by satellite to small rooftop antennas, avoiding the bandwidth problem that would be faced by over-the-air broadcasting. But special <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> receivers will be needed to see the enhanced picture. One of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> broadcasters' greatest fears is that the Japanese will begin exporting to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> HDTV video cassette recorders and receiver sets that would not receive over-the-air broadcast signals. `` We're fooling ourselves if we do n't think the people in the video cassette, cable and movie industries are going to take advantage of that,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, which is developing a system that improves picture quality though not as significantly as the Japanese HDTV system. `` Broadcasters could be put out of business or severely hurt if we take too long'' to meet the competition with an improved television picture, he said. But <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>'s report said the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public is unlikely to rush out to buy <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sets, which are expected to cost upwards of $ 3,500 when first introduced. The Media Lab study, admittedly `` an early experiment,'' was conducted in a shopping mall in <LOCATION> Danvers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, in early December 1987. For 30 minutes, a total of 613 randomly selected shoppers, in groups of five to 20, watched a variety of programs on conventional and <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sets. Though viewers could usually see a difference in picture quality between the two sets and overall liked HDTV more, they preferred a conventional picture for some of the programming, the study found.
</TEXT>
