<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> opened <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to Americans in the early 1970s. Now his son-in-law is opening <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to more and better advertising billboards. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s eagerness to put up more billboards is a sign of progress in the Communist nation, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said Monday in announcing a deal between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` If you're going to have a market-oriented economy, the most important thing is free passing of information, and advertising is a big part of that,'' <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, a finance lawyer and the husband of <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, acted as a go-between on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION>, which bills itself as the world's largest outdoor advertising company. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Media </PERSON> will give the Chinese advice on such matters as standardizing the sizes of billboards, upgrading its paint and attracting business from non-Chinese advertisers. `` An initiative like this, like sports or arts, transcends advertising or business. It goes to the germ of our being,'' said <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, the company's 36-year-old president and chief executive. With more than 1 billion consumers and only about 7,000 billboards, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is `` a little more naked'' than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> said, meaning that each advertising message has more impact. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> hopes to increase its number of billboards to 10,000 within five years, said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Guihong </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for almost all Chinese advertising billboards. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> is leading a group of Chinese advertising officials in a nine-day, six-city tour of <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations. Others on the tour include regional officials from <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nanjing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>. Outdoor advertising accounts for about 25 percent of advertising expenditures in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, compared to less than 2 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Media </PERSON> said. One reason is that Chinese characters can be understood by all literate Chinese regardless of the language or dialect they speak. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said he approached <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s group last year on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION>. He said the contact was a sidelight to the main purpose of his visit, which was to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as an emissary for former President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, who wanted to ascertain whether economic reforms were continuing. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said large-character posters are protected by the Chinese constitution. `` It used to be a political message,'' he said. `` Now the message is an advertising message.'' <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> declined to say how <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> would be paid for its services. He said the matter was still under negotiation. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Media </PERSON> will act as exclusive adviser to the Chinese on all outdoor advertising joint venture operations. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> founded <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Media </PERSON> at age 18 and remains its majority shareholder. The company swelled from a three-market operation into a $ 200 million-a-year giantwhen he engineered the $ 710 million acquisition of the assets of Foster and <PERSON> Kleiser </PERSON> from <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986.
