<HEAD>Japanese Trade Deficit Declines From 1987 Level, Widens From March
Figure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus continued to decline from year-earlier levels in March, although it widened from February's surplus, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday The surplus totaled $ 7.458 billion, down from $ 8.050 billion in March 1987, bu up from $ 5.238 billion the previous month. After seasonal adjustment, the surplus came to $ 6.552 billion, up from $ 6.479 billion in the previous month. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> registered a trade surplus of $ 3.4 billion with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, down from $ 3.77 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials characterized the figures as encouraging because of the year-to-year decline. The continuing shrinkage in the latest report was attributed to the high yen, which has slowed the growth of exports while boosting the yen's purchasing power and the value of imports flowing into the country. Imports surged much faster than exports, rising 35 percent to $ 15.21 billion from $ 11.26 billion a year earlier. Exports grew by a comparatively muted 17.4 percent to $ 22.67 billion from $ 19.31 billion a year earlier. Seasonally adjusted imports in the month dipped 3.9 percent to $ 14.76 billion from $ 15.36 billion in February, while adjusted exports inched down 2.4 percent to $ 21.31 billion from $ 21.84 billion. Exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rose 15.8 percent to $ 7.17 billion, while American imports rose 55.8 percent to $ 3.77 billion. Motor vehicle imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> soared 112.7 percent from a year earlier to $ 20.01 million. Food imports rose 47.1 percent to $ 805.1 million, while textile imports surged 87.8 percent to $ 78.6 million. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s exports of passenger vehicles to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rose 56 percent to $ 1.29 billion. Overall electrical machinery exports were up 11.4 percent to $ 1.57 billion, although television set exports fell 23 percent to $ 27.38 million.
