<HEAD>Irving Posts 84 Percent Profit Jump in 1st-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its first-quarter profit jumped 83 percent as tax benefits combined with strong growth in interest income and other gains more than offset a rise in costs. The company, which is fighting a hostile takeover bid from <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said its profit rose to $ 52.4 million, or $ 2.71 a share, in the first quarter compared with $ 28.6 million, or $ 1.51 a share, a year earlier. Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said the results included $ 12.3 million in tax benefits related to the loan-loss provisions that the company took in 1987 in anticipation of problems in collecting some Third World loans. Net interest income rose 12 percent to $ 146.9 million from $ 131.2 million a year earlier as the difference between what the bank paid in interest to obtain funds and what it received on its money widened in the banking company's favor. In the quarter, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> took a provision for credit losses of $ 19.6 million in 1988 compared with $ 21.8 million in 1987. That left its loan loss allowance at $ 696.5 million, or 4.38 percent of loans, compared with $ 224.8 million, or 1.62 percent of loans, a year earlier. Noninterest income increased 16 percent to $ 119 million from $ 102.6 million a year earlier, including a 24 percent rise in trust income. Securities trading generated revenue of $ 6.3 million in contrast with a loss of $ 2.8 million a year earlier. Noninterest expenses rose 11 percent to $ 179 million, including a 10 percent rise in salary and employee benefits. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> said earlier this month that it expects to earn $ 234 million in all of 1988 in contrast to a loss of $ 193.2 million a year earlier. It is trying to convince its shareholders to reject <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.08 billion tender offer of cash and securities for all of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s stock. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> is offering 1.575 shares of its own stock and $ 15 a share in cash for each of the 18.4 million shares of Irving stock that it does n't already own. But <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> has argued that its advisers rate the offer as inadequate.
