<HEAD>Boeing Plans News Conference on Reports of Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> declined Monday to comment on reports that four major airlines had reported defects in the aerospace company's 747 and 767 widebody jets. The problems reportedly ranged from wrong parts to incorrectly installed firefighting systems. <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial airplane division, deflected questions about the reports, saying the company planned to hold a news conference Tuesday to discuss the matter. The newspaper accounts said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had received complaints of defects from <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that All Nippon, a Japanese domestic carrier, disclosed it told <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> of several instances of poor workmanship in 747 and 767 airliners, mostly on newly delivered planes. The problems included a wing flap disintegrating in flight on the first day of service, smoke from a misassembled power unit that caused an emergency landing, and problems in a fire extinguisher system, All Nippon said. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted by the newspaper as saying a jetliner `` is a big complicated piece of machinery.'' The complaints were `` isolated instances that should n't happen,'' he said `` We're gon na bust our butt to make sure they do n't happen again.'' <PERSON> Yoshiyuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Funatsu </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president, told the <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION> that problems with defects had been increasing recently at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. He said that while many had been minor, some had safety ramifications, although none of the defects had caused accidents. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' senior vice president for operations, told the newspaper the company's maintenance crews had found faulty fire-suppression systems in the cargo holds of three 767-200s. The system pipes fire-fighting chemicals to the forward and aft compartments of the cargo hold. `` The pipes were misrouted,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` If you light them off for the forward belly system they go off in the rear.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said that after being informed of the problem by American, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> found one faulty system on its production line and <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> found several in their planes. Last week, it was reported that <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Susumu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaji </PERSON> had complained of manufacturing mistakes in a March 30 letter to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON>. Besides the fire extinguisher system, the airline complained about engine temperature sensors being installed in reverse order in a 747, which would cause temperature gauges to register for the wrong engines. In its Saturday editions, the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published excerpts from a letter from D.K. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>' chief engineer for technical and quality services, to <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Condit </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> inspectors at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s plant found problems in their jets ranging from missing fasteners to wrong or missing parts. One missing part caused the floor of a jet to bow so much that a main deck cargo power drive unit would not work, the Times said. `` My quality inspectors can only properly inspect a very small proportion of each aircraft,'' <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> wrote. `` They should never ever come across ... missing fasteners, missing parts, cracks, bodged rivets, fasterners fitted the wrong way round. Yet we find instances of some of these on every aircraft.''
