<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix typo in slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Says Chrysler Plant Closing To Cost Taxpayers $209 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s planned closing of its <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> auto plant would cost $ 209 million in welfare and unemployment benefits, along with lost taxes, for the first two years after the shutdown, a union-commissioned study concluded Monday. The analysis by the <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> estimated that the plant's closing would cost federal, state and local governments a total of $ 38,000 for each unemployed <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> worker. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced in January it plans to end auto production at <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> by Sept. 30, resulting in the layoffs of 5,500 workers. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> took over the plant last year as part of its purchase of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Of about the two dozen studies that we've done, that's the highest figure we've ever come up with,'' <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON>, MCLR research director, told a news conference at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 72 headquarters. <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> said the study, which was commissioned by the union local, was based on a previous <ORGANIZATION> MCLR </ORGANIZATION> study in 1985 but used more comprehensive welfare and employment figures from the state, <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION> counties and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. It estimated that the plant's closing would result in $ 62.4 million in unemployment compensation, $ 54.5 million in lost federal income tax revenue, $ 26 million in lost Social Security tax revenue, $ 21.4 million in welfare expenditures and $ 17 million in lost state sales and excise tax revenue. <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> has threatened to sue <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, claiming the Detroit-based automaker broke a promise to keep the plant open for five years. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they may have been overly optimistic when negotiating with the state for improvements and job training funds, but have repeatedly denied making any such promise. The study indicated that 53.1 percent of the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> workers would still be unemployed two years after the plant's closing. In addition, the study estimated that 9,796 other workers in the state would be dislocated by the shutdown. Most of those jobs would be in companies that supply <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> as well as people in retail, service and other jobs supported by the buying power of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers. `` In an economy like this, the absorbtion rate just is n't there. If jobs are n't there, people are n't going to get re-employed,'' <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> said. He said the figures for <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> were higher than those in other communities hit by large plant shutdowns because of several different factors in the southeastern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> economy and in the status of unionized <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers. Among the differences he cited: _ <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> has an above average unemployment rate which has remained above the national average for several years _ The area is strongly dependent on employment at the plant More than one-third of the area's total jobs would be lost with the shutdown. _ <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers make above average salaries and wages, $ 29,120, and have benefits that many other potential employers in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> do not have _ Unionized workers in general have a harder time finding new employment <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> said the study also estimated that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers would experience a loss in living standards within the first two years. With welfare and compensation benefits and new employment, the worker's average income in the second year would still decline by 77.5 percent, he said. Local 72 negotiator <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said the union commissioned the study as a public service. `` Some people in the public perceive this as a problem for the workers in the plant and do n't realize it's going to cost them a lot of money also,'' he said. <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said the study would be sent to state and local officials to aid in negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
