<HEAD>Posts 55 Percent Rise in 1st-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dow Jones & amp; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its first-quarter profit climbed 55.3 percent from a year ago as its revenue rose 37.5 percent and the company reported a huge gain on the sale of a book publishing subsidiary <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, the publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and Barron's, said its profit amounted to $ 103.6 million, or $ 1.08 a share, in the three months ended March 31 compared with $ 66.7 million, or 69 cents a share, a year ago. First-quarter revenue rose to $ 392.5 million from $ 285.6 million a year earlier. The latest results included an after-tax gain of $ 64.5 million from the previously reported sale of the book publisher <ORGANIZATION> Richard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Irwin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 135 million. First-quarter results in 1987 included an after-tax gain of $ 29.4 million, or 30 cents a share, from the sale of the company's 18.9 percent interest in the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. Excluding those gains for each period, earnings were up 4.8 percent to $ 39.2 million in the latest quarter compared with $ 37.4 million a year earlier. Operating income for the quarter rose 54.2 percent to $ 91.1 million from $ 59.1 million in 1987. The company said the increase in operating income reflected contributions from <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the electronic financial information service that is 56 percent owned by <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, and the continued growth of Dow Jones' community newspapers. Operating income in the business publications segment fell 22.7 percent to $ 32.6 million as revenue slipped 4.6 percent in the quarter, partly reflecting lower levels of financial advertising in the wake of the October stock market crash. Operating income from the information services segment which includes Telerate results more than fourfold to $ 54.3 million as revenue more than tripled. <ORGANIZATION> Ottaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the community services segment, said its operating income rose 3.7 percent to $ 8.5 million as revenue rose 11.5 percent.
