<HEAD>BankAmerica Adopts Takeover Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which bitterly fought off one hostile takeover bid two years ago and could become a target again, adopted a takeover defense plan on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors said the preferred share purchase rights plan was intended to protect shareholders `` in the event of partial tender offers, squeeze-outs, and other abusive tactics to gain control of <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> without paying all stockholders a premium.'' The plan would make a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive by allowing <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> common shareholders to acquire a new issue of preferred stock in the event a party acquired 20 percent of the company's common shares or launched a tender offer to acquire 20 percent or more. <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's third-largest bank holding company, following No. 1 <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, both of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. A.W. <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, said the plan was not in reaction to any specific buyout proposal. He noted that hundreds of other companies had adopted similar plans. <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> stock closed down 12 -LCB- cents to $ 11 a share Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, waged a lengthy and bitter hostile bid for <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> beginning in 1986, but gave up its chase last year in the face of a major <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> restructuring that the suitor said diminished the value of its target. `` I do n't know why they took this action at this point, except that maybe the time to do it is when you do n't need to,'' <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco-based </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sutro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> `` Maybe they just want to be prepared.'' Nevertheless, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> added, if the company did not have further major problems with its troubled Third World debt portfolio it might be able to produce a string of profitable performances that could make it an attractive target. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> announced the formation of three regional capital markets operations to serve <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Each will be responsible for trading, merchant banking and investment banking activities in its respective region. `` We're reorganizing our operation from product-oriented to geography-oriented,'' said bank spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
