<HEAD>Johnson &amp; Johnson, Playtex Drop Negotiations For Playtex
Subsidiary Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have terminated negotiations aimed at selling the <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> business to <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, the companies said Monday. In a news release, the companies cited difficulties in structuring and completing the definitive agreements for the transaction as reasons for ending the talks. <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> said it intended to continue operating building the Family Products business, which is a major maker of tampons and also produces toothbrushes, household gloves and disposable baby nursers. `` The business had a highly successful year in 1987 and is off to a strong start in 1988,'' <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smilow </PERSON>, chairman and CEO of <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION>, said in the release. On Feb. 16, <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said it had agreed to pay $ 726 million for <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION>. Industry analysts said at the time that the addition of <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> would give the health care giant more than 30 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tampon market, of which it already has about 6 percent with the O.B. brand tampon. <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> is one of three operating subsidiaries of <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION>, itself once part of <ORGANIZATION> BCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the company formed by the April 1986 leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Beatrice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos </ORGANIZATION>. The Family Products Division accounts for half <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION>'s sales and 70 percent of its profits, <PERSON> Smilow </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION>'s other two divisions are <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jhirmack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of hair care products, and <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apparel </ORGANIZATION>, a leading worldwide manufacturer of bras, girdles and pantyhose. Proceeds from the sale of the Family Products Division would have gone towards paying off debt incurred in the December 1986 leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> from BCI, <PERSON> Smilow </PERSON> said when the proposed deal was announced. <PERSON> Smilow </PERSON> said in the release Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> would continue its efforts to sell the Jhirmack division.
