<SECOND>AM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steelmaker Allowed To Sell Most Of Idled Monessen Mill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can sell most of its idled mill in <LOCATION> Monessen </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a federal bankruptcy judge ruled Monday. The $ 18.1 million deal, approved by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, is unusual because both companies are reorganizing under federal bankruptcy laws. The deal does not include a $ 120 million rail mill that is to be sold in three months by the federal agency that financed and later foreclosed on it. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>'s offer, which edged out four other bids, was for <LOCATION> Monessen </LOCATION>'s coke ovens, raw steelmaking facilities and continuous bloom caster, a piece of equipment that produces semi-finished products. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> has until May 15 to complete the purchase, but has reserved the right to back out of the deal if the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and Judge <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Teitelbaum </PERSON> refuse to grant temporary relief from pollution control standards imposed on coke operations at the <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> mill. Attorneys for <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> and its creditors said <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s offer was best, partly because the steelmaker would provide a ready market for the coke. They also said <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> would be better able to press any financial claims against another company that was reorganizing under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law than against one that was not. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sieckman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive, said his company's plans to reopen the coke ovens will bring back about 150 jobs. The ovens were idled in June 1986 but kept partially fired to prevent their brick linings from deteriorating. A restart of the operations also would enable <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> to recall about 90 to 100 of its own workers who were laid off last week when a shortfall of coke _ a necessary ingredient in steelmaking _ caused the company to temporarily idle one of its two blast furnaces. <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> purchases coke on the open market, but has been unable to fill its requirements.
